FROM (VALUES
  ('cmnn87aur001zcnded94p6yju', $grulla$In the real world as much as in anime and manga, everything is about balance. Sometimes, when you have impulsive and relentless characters, you also need a shy and cautious one in order to show the audience both sides of the coin and make the story feel more real. Likewise, these shy characters who think before they act generally offer the best opportunities for development, allowing them, through effort and motivation, to break out of those birdcages in which they encase themselves and to reach new heights. In Hunter X Hunter the best example of this is Shoot, who, despite being overshadowed by the rest of the characters in the Chimera Ant arc, is probably one of the most developed characters, and has one of the most interesting abilities of the arc.

Shoot has a shy personality and is often afraid to seize the opportune moments to attack an enemy. His prudence makes him a good contrast to Knuckle, since he counters the latter's impulsiveness with his colder and more analytical mind. He was willing to let thousands of people die for the sake of saving billions of others, showing himself to be someone Machiavellian. However, when the fight with Youpi begins, he is inspired by Gon and is able to unleash his full power, overcoming his shyness and his wounds.

We tend to think of Hunters as people who love to fight in order to achieve their goals; however, Shoot is a great example of the opposite. He is someone who, by his own confession, does not like to hurt others, not even if they deserve it, and fears for his own well-being more than most of his companions. This can make him feel like someone hesitant, and maybe he is, but it is his ability to overcome this and give everything of himself to protect his companions despite not having this tendency naturally that makes him so inspiring.

In terms of power level, Shoot has demonstrated remarkable combat prowess by briefly facing Youpi, a Royal Guard, on his own, although he suffered nearly fatal wounds. Additionally, with Knuckle's help, he was able to seal the manipulated body of Kite, who was fighting without restrictions of any kind, an extremely notable achievement. His low confidence in his abilities has often been an obstacle for him, but Gon's example allowed him to discover his own determination, which enabled him to attack Youpi without worrying about his own life. He is very observant, noticing Killua's electric attack before he could carry it out. His Nen abilities allow him to effectively compensate for the loss of his left arm.

Perhaps Shoot's most important physical attribute is his speed, since he can move so quickly that the slightest distraction from Killua allowed him to close the distance between them before the young Hunter could react, although he managed to avoid the subsequent blows when he was not under the effects of his brother's conditioning. Shoot noticed electricity around Killua's hands and withdrew before Killua's ability could connect. While flying on his hand, he becomes extremely fast, dodging and redirecting many of Youpi's attacks despite their number, and even managed to touch the Royal Guard's body once.

Some of Shoot's most overlooked abilities are his spatial reasoning and balance, both key to being able to use his ability at the level he uses it, and despite being someone who does not like to fight and fears getting hurt, his stamina and resistance to pain are remarkable, being able to keep fighting after Youpi's attacks to his leg and after suffering lethal wounds all over his body.

Finally, Shoot is one of the most expert Hunters in pursuit and hunting, being able to follow his prey's tracks expertly and better than most other Hunters.

When it comes to his Nen, Shoot is a Manipulator*. He specializes in manipulating three hands that he uses as controllable projectiles or as distractions to land a blow and activate Hotel Rafflesia. The repeated disappearances and reappearances of his birdcage, and especially of the hands, seem to suggest that they are conjured. Since he does not like to hurt others, Shoot made his main Nen ability one that can only be used by injuring someone, so he would resort to it when he had no other option and, therefore, would have no qualms about using it. Another of his abilities allows him to convert small objects into two-dimensional impressions in his right hand. He is an extremely capable user of Zetsu who went unnoticed by Gon and Killua for nearly a month. He also appears to be competent in Shu, since he is able to imbue his floating hands with aura. During the attack on the Chimera Ants, following a hunch, Shoot covered his right eye, which, together with the thrill of feeling cornered, increased his strength, indicating that he is potentially a user of Nen restrictions.

Going into more detail on his Hatsu, which can be a little confusing to understand, Shoot calls it Impression Conversion, which uses his Nen to convert pocket-sized three-dimensional objects into impressions on the palm of his hand, as well as returning them to their normal state without damage. It seems that Shoot can maintain the effect for at least several days. This allows him to use two sub-techniques, the first of these, and the one we most often see him use, being the floating hands.

Shoot can conjure three floating hands, which he then controls with Manipulation. He can coat them with aura and use them as projectiles capable of surrounding and striking the target, but also as distractions to get close to the opponent and activate Hotel Rafflesia. Shoot has great control over the hands, which he can position to exploit the blind spots created by Hotel Rafflesia. The aura around a single hand allows him to have enough power to damage Killua, though not enough to hurt him significantly, as well as to come out unharmed from Killua's attacks, both physical and through his yo-yos. During the fight against Youpi, Shoot was able to control the hands with such precision, speed and power that they were able to defend against the Royal Guard's tentacles. He could also stand on one of them to fly quickly, which he considers his special technique. Despite the fact that Shoot always uses the hands together with the cage of Hotel Rafflesia, the two abilities seem distinct.

But now that I mention it, what is Hotel Rafflesia?

This second ability allows him, through physical contact, to steal specific parts of the opponent's body through physical contact, shrinking them and teleporting them to his birdcage, potentially until their entire body is sealed. The affected body part is replaced by a dark mist. Although the opponent feels no pain and is not actually injured, Shoot's ability can throw their mind into chaos. Furthermore, by targeting the eyes, Shoot can create blind spots to exploit in successive attacks. To deactivate the ability, Shoot opens the door of the cage, allowing the trapped target to walk out, after which they return to their normal size. It deactivates automatically if Shoot loses consciousness. Given that the size reduction is associated with Conjuration, it seems that Hotel Rafflesia also incorporates elements of this type of Nen. Its teleportation component may mean the additional involvement of Emission.

Shoot's abilities are interesting because, in addition to being useful in situations that are not only combat but also support, they are abilities that contrast greatly with his personality, which is completely intentional. You see, Shoot is one of the few characters in Hunter x Hunter who knows his flaws and limitations perfectly, and he uses his technique as a way to force himself to set aside his shyness and to hurt others. This technique, which requires stealing others' bodies from them and striking them from multiple directions, is as much a torture for his opponents as for himself, and only after Gon's help and inspiration did he finally manage to reach his potential.

Sometimes you hear criticism of Shoot for his indecision, shyness and cowardice. But these critics do not stop to think about the effects that these qualities have in an arc where most of the characters are overly impulsive and decisive, and who, if they would only stop to think for a second, could obtain a better result. This, added to his rapid development and the lesson his character teaches the audience, makes him someone worthy of participating in this incredible arc and of being regarded as an essential character for this wonderful Shonen.$grulla$, $grulla$Shoot$grulla$),
  ('cmnn87als001xcndedn08xqae', $grulla$The ability to heal with the Reverse Cursed Technique is extremely rare and coveted in the world of Jujutsu Kaisen. The control required to perform it, along with how difficult it is to explain how to achieve it, makes it one of the hardest abilities to master, and only a handful of sorcerers are capable of using it at will. What's interesting is that you don't need to be a genius on Yuta's level to pull it off, and we even have a relatively low-ranked sorcerer who is a specialist in this technique. Of course, I'm talking about Shoko Ieiri, the complement to Geto and Gojo's group at the Tokyo Jujutsu school, and who is currently the academy's healer.

Shoko is a very relaxed and carefree person, especially compared to Ijichi's nervous attitude and Gojo's excessively playful one. As a student alongside Gojo and Geto, she lets the two of them fight and simply removes herself from the situation while calmly climbing the ranks at school. This makes her the perfect complement to these two special grade sorcerers, since she is content to just work behind the scenes and stay out of their way.

Shoko doesn't seem to take any situation very seriously in general during her years at the Jujutsu Academy. She openly smokes in public despite obviously being a high school student, and this habit stayed with her into adulthood. Even after Geto betrayed them, Shoko was able to have a casual conversation with him about what he did. She feels completely comfortable asking him about the accusations and even called him childish for being in a bad mood because no one understands him. She even called Gojo to come confront Geto right in front of him without any fear for her own life.

As the school doctor, Shoko seems to take her job seriously and acts in a very stoic manner. While Gojo was visibly upset over Yuji's death, Shoko kept her personal feelings out of the situation and just wanted to perform an autopsy, pointing out that Gojo was being more emotional than usual. It's hinted that Shoko has tried to quit her smoking habit many times, but the stress of her work as a healer probably makes it harder. She stated that she was "nostalgic for her high school days" when she was noticed smoking again in Shibuya, showing that she still thinks about and cares about what happens to her former classmates and the new students.

As one of the few healers at the Jujutsu Academy and a user of the Reverse Cursed Technique, Shoko is a valuable asset to her colleagues and students alike, and she has saved many sorcerers even on the brink of death. She stays composed on the battlefield and doesn't worry about being discovered in Shibuya despite the danger of being a high-value target.

In terms of power level, it's clear that Shoko is not the combat type of sorcerer, but she still participates in missions with Gojo and Geto while training as a student, which indicates she possesses some kind of combat abilities. Shoko doesn't show the ability to use normal cursed techniques, but she clearly possesses the rare ability to use the Reverse Cursed Technique. She can apply it to others to regenerate lost limbs and heal wounds, something not even Gojo can do. However, when asked how it works, Shoko can't put it into words that could effectively teach someone else how to use it. This shows that she uses it instinctively and doesn't really understand it, which limits its effectiveness.

Shoko possesses the necessary knowledge of a traditional doctor and also has the skills to save her comrades at any given moment. She is invaluable to the sorcerers of the Jujutsu Academy as the only healer of this kind besides Yuta, who is more valuable in combat. When Nanami is injured by Mahito in their first fight, he retreats to the Academy to receive treatment from Shoko. Ijichi and Ino would have died if they weren't treated immediately by her during the Shibuya Incident as well.

Her skills as a doctor also make Shoko very knowledgeable in the field of sorcery in relation to biology. When dissecting two transfigured humans, Shoko is the one who is able to discover that they aren't actually cursed spirits but humans transfigured by a cursed technique. Shoko is also the one who correctly theorizes that the Culling Game's cursed technique removal penalty will affect the players' brains and end their lives as a result.

Even though Shoko doesn't know how to explain it properly, there is a very clear idea of how the Reverse Cursed Technique works.

Basically, this technique processes negative energy into positive energy by taking two sources of cursed energy and multiplying them together. As a result, the energy that destroys becomes energy that creates, and negative energy becomes positive. Despite sounding simple enough, producing positive energy is extremely complex and difficult for most jujutsu users to perform.

Positive energy can be used for various purposes, but most commonly for healing. Cursed energy comes from negative emotions, which are not suitable for healing living beings. However, cursed spirits, which are made up of cursed energy, don't require the Reverse Cursed Technique to heal. Jujutsu sorcerers mainly use positive energy to generate new flesh and heal human bodies. However, even using the Reverse Cursed Technique to heal wounds can sometimes leave a scar. While very few sorcerers can use the Reverse Cursed Technique, there are even fewer who emit it to heal people other than themselves, like Shoko. However, when used to heal others, the Reverse Cursed Technique is less than half as efficient as when healing oneself.

The Reverse Cursed Technique can even be used to replenish a depleted cursed technique after using a Domain Expansion. However, one cannot heal their body at the same time as their cursed technique, and this is something too advanced for Shoko, something we've only seen in the most powerful sorcerers.

The Reverse Cursed Technique can also be used to heal wounds on the soul; however, this requires the user to be able to perceive the shape of the soul, something that Shoko unfortunately is incapable of.

In conclusion, Shoko isn't really the strongest character, not even within her own specialty. However, the special thing is that her ability to use the Reverse Cursed Technique to heal others makes her invaluable to the Jujutsu sorcerers, and someone without whom not only our protagonist but a large part of the cast would have ceased to exist. So we should give this behind-the-scenes support character her due, and maybe understand her and let her smoke a cigarette every now and then to relax.$grulla$, $grulla$Shoko$grulla$),
  ('cmnn87ad0001vcndex5ed0jav', $grulla$The world of the Yokai in Dandadan is one of sadness, tragedy, and horror. These Japanese monsters seem to exist to torment the living in different ways, whether those who interfere with their territory, or those who, for one reason or another, catch their attention. However, we have seen how the Yokai are not necessarily evil, but rather peculiar when it comes to their moral code and their decisions, acting in emotional and not very logical ways, yet with reasons that are not entirely far-fetched. In particular, those Yokai who were born from the strong emotions of living people seem to have unique and specific goals, which makes them easier to understand. We have already seen several Yokai with different motivations and personalities, but I think there is no better example of a Yokai with clear motivations than Acrobatic Silky, or Akusara, the Yokai who lends her powers to Aira.

When she was alive, Acrobatic Silky was a woman in debt who had to work multiple jobs, including serving as a prostitute, working as a janitor, and as a cashier at a store, all while caring for her only daughter, whom she loved deeply. After deciding to use part of the money she earned to buy her daughter a dress, the men to whom she owed money came to her house to collect what she had, beat her brutally, and kidnapped her daughter. The mother desperately chased the van in which the men took her daughter away, but it was in vain, as she fell to the ground and watched helplessly as the van disappeared from her sight. In her despair, combined with the knowledge that she would never see her daughter again, the mother performed one last dance on the rooftop before throwing herself into the void, with her final thoughts focused on her daughter.

The woman's spirit wandered through the city for an unknown amount of time and lost the memories of when she was alive as she became a Yokai, although she felt that she had lost something very important. While she was in the streets, a little girl named Aira Shiratori approached her after mistaking her for her deceased mother, but left with her father upon realizing her mistake. This misunderstanding led the woman to believe that in her previous life she had been Aira's mother, developing an obsession with protecting her. This obsession transformed her into the Yokai we call Acrobatic Silky or Acrosara. She spent the following ten years stalking Aira until she could finally see her again and call her "mother."

Akusara took the form of an extremely tall woman with gray skin, long limbs, and long, silky, jet-black hair. She had a narrow face with sunken eyes, wrinkles on the upper part of her face, and a permanent smile painted with lipstick that exposed her large teeth. She wore red polish on her fingernails and toenails, with long nails on her hands. She walked barefoot while wearing a red wide-brimmed hat and a red dress (similar to the one she had bought for her daughter), with a violet collar that accentuated her long neck. At first, her face looked as it did in life, until the day she met Aira and transformed into a complete Yokai.

Due to her tragic past, in which her daughter was taken from her, Acrosara is a yokai with a desperate need to find a child to love and who would call her "mother." Her main fixation is Aira, after becoming delusional in believing that she had been her mother in life, which led her to obsess over the idea of having her all to herself. Her intentions were also driven by her maternal instincts, as she was willing to sacrifice her own aura to revive Aira, and even tore off her own jaw to assure Momo that she would not try to eat her.

Of course, as her name indicates, both the original human and the Yokai have considerable confidence in their acrobatic and ballet abilities, using these movements as their main martial art. Her exceptional speed, agility, and reflexes allow her to react in time and dodge a fast charging attack from Okarun, who uses Turbo Granny's speed.

In addition, her leg strength is incredible, easily able to send humans flying with a simple kick and able to break free from Momo's psychic force.

Her endurance is a point we cannot overlook either, as she has shown us that she is resilient enough to get back on her feet after taking damage from Okarun's strongest blow and being sent flying through a building.

The main advantage of Akusara's special ability is that it allows her to extend her hair to considerable lengths and manipulate it at will. Her hair can entangle anything in her surroundings, which allows her to capture and throw her opponents. In addition, it helps her traverse difficult terrain at extremely high speeds.

A significant vulnerability of Akusara's acrobatic abilities is her susceptibility to fire, as this could scorch her hair, hindering the process of untangling the objects to which it is attached.

Together with her acrobatic movements, Akusara uses her hair to entangle her surroundings. This allows her to immobilize her enemies, trap them, and even strike them by using her hair against other objects. Her hair can also act as additional limbs, allowing her to grab objects from her surroundings to use as weapons. Her hair is so long and flexible that it can be used as traps, to hinder the movement of her enemies in enclosed spaces.

The inspirations behind this Yokai are quite interesting, as they seem to mix legends from two distinct cultures. Akusara's abilities and appearance are directly inspired by the Japanese urban legend of the same name, about a mysterious entity that resembles a tall and slender woman, with pale skin, dressed in an elegant red dress and a matching wide-brimmed hat. Her long, silky black hair and her unsettling presence make her unforgettable. She is frequently seen in large cities performing dangerous acts, such as dancing atop buildings, moving erratically across distant rooftops, and leaping from them like an acrobat.

After her performance, the spirit vanishes without a trace, leaving onlookers bewildered and terrified. According to the legend, those who witness Akusara's acrobatics are cursed, doomed to experience misfortune or even death.

However, her personality and story more closely resemble the Mexican legend of La Llorona, or the woman who weeps profusely for her lost daughter and is cursed to wander in search of her for all eternity.

This Yokai may be the most interesting in terms of her story, as we see it in its entirety and it allows us to understand that there is more to these Japanese monsters than meets the eye. Additionally, her relationship with Aira is the deepest and friendliest of all the possessed humans, which makes her a character easier to empathize with than Turbo Granny or Evil Eye. Of course, her inspirations are as clear and interesting as those of the other Yokai, but it is impressive how much attention has been paid to a character who is relatively secondary as far as the overall story is concerned, and once again it demonstrates the hidden genius of Dandadan.$grulla$, $grulla$Acrobatic Silky$grulla$),
  ('cmnn87a3h001tcndeqowwdljm', $grulla$Throughout the journey of One Piece, many stories are told that make us think from the deepest part of our being, and even cause us to reevaluate ourselves on a personal level. But in my opinion, of everything that has been told in the anime so far, no story comes close to the impact of the evolution of our favorite Straw Hat chef, Black Leg Sanji.

Not everything about Sanji's character is perfect. Oda has given him certain personality traits that neither I nor many fans agree with, particularly his unbridled perversion, which at times even contradicts a part of his personality, the kind of knight in shining armor he is with women. However, I would venture to say that this is not his main struggle in psychological terms, but rather an entirely secondary one. Sanji's central struggle is even more fundamental, and it is rooted in the nature of his family and his childhood: what do you do when everyone around you is inhuman and you are the only human with emotions? And what would happen if, over time, you saw the possibility of becoming someone inhuman yourself, and how would you deal with that?

Sanji is one of the characters who has received the most flashbacks in the work, not only with his original story alongside Zeff, surviving on the island with no food, but also with the entire story of Germa and of his family as the children of the mad scientist Judge. To recall the context: Germa 66 is a group of villains who literally stepped out of a cartoon, using technology to clone superhumans and create cyborg children with superhuman abilities and no emotions. Judge managed to turn Germa into the largest group of military mercenaries in the world of One Piece, single-handedly winning countless wars in the North Blue. All of Judge's children, from Yonji on down, are superhumans capable of doing anything, since they lack any kind of empathy. Well, perhaps there is one small exception. But do you know who is not just an exception, but someone who goes completely against everything that Ichiji, Yonji, and even Judge himself represent? Sanji.

Sanji, the third son of Judge and Sora, was born without the superhuman abilities of his brothers, and on top of that, he was born the most human of the entire family, having empathy even for the smallest animals. He grew up watching how the normal thing around him was to be useless for not being like his brothers, yet somehow instinctively understanding the difference between good and evil, and deciding for himself, despite all the influence of his father and his own brothers, to do good. A large part of this came from the influence of his mother, who, despite being with Judge, also seems to be an empathetic and sensitive person, and who surely taught Sanji the difference between what the rest of his family does and the broader morality of the world he lives in.

That is surely the origin of two key aspects of Sanji. One: his absolute empathy, being the only ray of sunlight in a world as dark and devastating as Germa. And two: his unconditional love and devotion to women, since the female gender was the only one that showed him appreciation and taught him that he was not completely useless. The love given to him by his mother Sora and by his sister Reiju at different moments in his life taught him that women are to be admired and protected, and that under no circumstances should he attack them or fight against them.

Sanji grew up seeing the rest of his family as inhuman monsters who tortured everyone around them, even him, for lacking the abilities and mindset of his brothers. To Judge, Sanji is trash, and to Sanji, Judge and his experiments are subhuman, complete demons. This defines his character as someone who not only seeks humanity through his demonstrated empathy, shown when he grows up by his complete objectivity in everything that involves feeding someone, no matter whether they are good or evil, but who also seeks humanity as an absolute rejection of his birth family, going so far as to discard the Vinsmoke surname and to consider his adoptive father his only family. In the area where Sanji shows his love, the kitchen, Zeff was not just someone who taught him to cook, but an adoptive father who reinforced the main characteristics that Sanji demonstrates throughout the story: loyalty, empathy, calm, and chivalry. I think it is fair to say that without Zeff's influence, Sanji probably would not be the person he is today.

Throughout One Piece, Sanji has demonstrated a capacity to observe situations and to act in an intelligent and measured way in order to gain information or save his friends. Two perfect examples of this are when he had the conversation with Crocodile, extracting information from him, and when he infiltrated the train on the way to Enies Lobby, predicting that something was wrong with Robin. But it is only in the second part of the story, after the time skip, after Marineford, that we see the true depth of Sanji's humanity, and how at times he wavered between having to adopt his inhuman side, granted to him at birth by Judge's experiments. Specifically, the Whole Cake Island and Wano arcs show us this.

In Whole Cake, Sanji finds himself in a contradiction of his principles. On one hand, abandoning the Straw Hats, marrying Big Mom's daughter Pudding, and returning in a certain way to the wars of his family is the only way he sees to save the most important people in his life, giving himself up completely and selflessly. But on the other hand, this forces him to act like an inhuman being who does not think about the real feelings of his captain and his nakama. Nothing demonstrates this better than the fight between Sanji and Luffy, where Sanji shows his conviction to the point of attacking Luffy with all his strength to force him to stop chasing him, begging him in order to save him. This stubbornness is a demonstration of Sanji's distrust in the abilities of Luffy and the rest to find an alternative to solve the current problem, and it contradicts Sanji's apparent inhumanity with his real, human intentions. It is only when Pudding reveals her true self and Sanji's heart is completely broken, and faced with the complete confidence in Sanji's humanity that his captain Luffy holds despite the beating Sanji gave him, that he finally makes the decision to reject the path painted for him by his family and chooses to leave with his new family, his Straw Hats.

However, even after Whole Cake Island, there are residues of Germa's influence in Sanji's mind, and there is no better reminder of this than his Raid Suit, a tool of war created by Germa specifically for him, which ironically gives him the one power he has truly desired: to become invisible, even if it is for the reasons we like least about his character. This Power Ranger suit, and his ability to use it to become more effective, creates the same dilemma he lived through on Whole Cake Island. Yes, it is a reminder of the lack of humanity of his birth family, but at the same time it is a way to become stronger in order to defeat opponents who could threaten his new family. That is why Sanji does not discard it immediately, despite condemning what Germa does verbally.

It is in the fight against Queen in the middle of Onigashima that Sanji manages to break the barrier of his indecision between the human and the inhuman, and is truly free to make a place for himself among the wings of the Pirate King. In this fight, Queen is a reminder of Judge, being part of the same scientific group as him, and again and again he insists and pressures Sanji to show him the powers of the Raid Suit. Sanji refuses, again and again. But despite his rejection of the suit, his body begins to change, starting by showing the same physical improvements as the brothers he has always criticized: a hard, resistant body and the ability to recover his original form, giving him basically super endurance and resilience. Sanji immediately realizes that becoming an inhuman being is probably not something that is 100% within his control; it may be mere genetics. His desperation and confusion do not allow him to fight with all his strength against Queen, who represents that very influence causing the changes in his body. It even reaches the point where we are shown Queen's representation of what Germa is, giving them the powers of his brothers: he has the electric powers of Niji, he has the laser eyes that Ichiji has, and he has the kind of claw and superstrength that Yonji has, all the superpowers of his brothers.

It is only when Sanji, remembering the influence of his mother and his true nature and responsibility to his captain, who not only saved him multiple times from despair but also gave him a new family that understood and accepted him for who he is, that he manages to make a true decision, a profound decision rooted in the deepest part of his being: to destroy the Raid Suit, the reminder and his bond to Germa, and ironically to accept his inhuman future for the sake of the human he has to be in the present. Sanji decides to use the improvements in his body to create a hotter flame in the form of Ifrit, and even reaches the point of asking his rival Zoro for help so that he can fight with peace of mind, giving Zoro the trust to finish him off if at any moment he loses control. Sanji rejects inhumanity by accepting it, and in that moment he is free and reaches his true level of power, which allows him to defeat someone like Queen.

Sanji's very existence is a contradiction in itself. His birth and evolution owe a great deal to the genetics and inhuman science of Judge and Germa, yet at the same time he is one of the most human and empathetic people in all of One Piece, capable of even accepting the inhumanity he so abhors in order to keep his convictions and be the guardian angel that protects the entire crew. It is something similar to what Zeff did to save him when he was on that deserted island: he demonstrated a complete capacity to give himself up in order to save Sanji, a person he did not even appreciate that much. Sanji seems to be making a similar sacrifice, but with completely different motivations. In this case, what he wants to do is save the crew that has become his new family. A point we cannot forget is that Sanji even reaches the point of asking the last person he would ever want to ask for help, showing a humility that an inhuman being could never possess. And in the end, it all demonstrates that Black Leg Sanji has rejected the inhuman and is the most human of all of One Piece.$grulla$, $grulla$Sanji$grulla$),
  ('cmnn879ud001rcnde14drkkb9', $grulla$## The Banquet of Existence: The Anatomy of the King of Curses

Within the vast and often predictable structure of contemporary shonen, there exists an almost obsessive tendency to humanize evil. We search for the foundational trauma, the open wound that justifies the blaze, the "sad past" that allows us, somehow, to empathize with the monster. We want to believe that evil is a response to an external stimulus. And yet, Gege Akutami chose to hurl into the center of _Jujutsu Kaisen_ an anomaly that defies all logic of redemption: Ryomen Sukuna.

Sukuna is not a man who fell into darkness; he is the darkness that learned to walk, to cut, and, above all, to savor. He is not a villain with a thousand-year master plan to save the world from itself, nor a misunderstood martyr. He is a natural disaster with a consciousness of its own. We are speaking of a being who does not seek the world's validation, but who understands that the world is, quite simply, his playground and his personal slaughterhouse. Throughout this analysis, we will break down why Sukuna is not merely the most formidable antagonist in the work, but a philosophical representation of absolute hedonism and the solitude that perfection entails.

---

### I. The Aesthetics of Deformity: Beyond the Human

To understand Sukuna, we must first strip him of Yuji Itadori's skin. For much of the series, we saw him limited by a vessel that hated him, a cage of flesh and morality that tried to contain an ocean of malice. But Sukuna's true essence resides in his Heian Era form: a being of four arms, two faces, and a presence that distorts reality itself.

This anatomy is not a visual whim. In the world of sorcery, the body is the soul and the soul is the body. The four arms allow him to perform hand signs and incantations—the fundamental components of sorcery—without interrupting his flow of physical combat. It is maximum efficiency. While a normal sorcerer must choose between defending himself or attacking with his technique, Sukuna is an engine of perpetual motion.

But beyond the tactical advantage, his appearance is a statement of principle. Sukuna despises human limitation. His physical existence is a necessary "excess" because his will does not fit into a standard mold. He is the "artist" who needs more brushes than the natural body provides. Looking at his design, we see that Sukuna has left behind any pretense of belonging to society. He is his own society, his own god, and his own judge.

---

### II. The Gourmet's Philosophy: The World as Ingredient

What makes Sukuna truly terrifying is not his brute strength, but his perspective. His cursed technique is based on culinary concepts: _Cleave_ (Cortar) and _Dismantle_ (Desmantelar). For Sukuna, combat is not a struggle of ideals, it is a preparation. He sees his opponents not as equals, but as cuts of meat that must be filleted to see whether there is anything inside worth consuming.

This culinary hedonism is the key to his psychology. Sukuna lives for the moment, for the pleasure of the palate, for the ecstasy of a clean cut. In a world where sorcerers are driven by duty (like Nanami) or by guilt (like Itadori), Sukuna is driven by appetite. This is the purest form of freedom and, by extension, the most dangerous. You cannot reason with someone whose only goal is to satisfy a hunger that is, by definition, infinite.

Even his **Domain Expansion, Malevolent Shrine (Santuario Malévolo)**, reinforces this idea. Unlike almost any other domain seen in the series, Sukuna's has no barriers. It does not seal the enemy within a separate space. Instead, Sukuna "paints" his reality over the real world. It is an act of divine arrogance: I do not need to trap you, because there is no place in this world where you can hide from my reach. It is the shrine of a god who does not ask for worship, but who demands the sacrifice of everything that enters his radius of action.

---

### III. The Clash of Ideologies: The Vessel and the Contents

The relationship between Sukuna and Itadori is, perhaps, the most fascinating study in contrast in modern narrative. Normally, the "inner demon" trope (think of Naruto and Kurama, or Ichigo and his Hollow) ends in an uneasy truce or a heroic symbiosis. But Sukuna breaks this rule with unusual violence. He hates Itadori. Not with a respectful hatred, but with a deep disgust.

For Sukuna, Itadori represents everything he despises: self-sacrifice, concern for the "weak," and the idea that life has intrinsic value. That a "brat" with such ideals was capable of containing him was the greatest humiliation of his thousand-year existence. Sukuna did not want to cooperate with Yuji; he wanted to erase him.

When he finally manages to transfer himself into Megumi Fushiguro's body, he does not do it solely for the power of the Ten Shadows. He does it to destroy Itadori's spirit and to inhabit a body that, in its lineage and potential, is "worthy" of his majesty. By usurping Megumi, Sukuna commits the ultimate act of cruelty: he uses the face of a friend to murder all hope. It is here that we see that Sukuna does not merely seek to win, he seeks to shatter the moral structure of those around him.

---

### IV. Solitude at the Summit: Gojo Satoru vs. Ryomen Sukuna

The confrontation between Gojo and Sukuna was more than a battle of powers; it was a philosophical debate about solitude. Gojo Satoru, the "strongest" of the modern era, lived in a solitude born of isolation. He wanted others to reach him, he wanted to raise a generation that could walk by his side. His strength was a burden he tried to transform into a bridge.

Sukuna, on the contrary, embraced solitude as the natural state of excellence. For him, being at the summit means there is no one else, and that is fine. Gojo's defeat at the hands of Sukuna was not merely a matter of spatial techniques or Mahoraga's adaptations; it was the victory of absolute egotism over pedagogical altruism.

Sukuna demonstrated that his capacity for learning is his most lethal weapon. He is not a static being. Despite being a thousand years old, Sukuna remains a student of sorcery, analyzing and stealing concepts even in the midst of the most intense fight of his life. His victory over Gojo's "Infinity" was a poem to his tactical genius: he cut the world itself to reach the one who could not be touched. In that moment, Sukuna rose above the category of "curse" to become a fundamental law of the universe.

---

### V. The Love of Calamity

One of Sukuna's strangest and most profound dialogues occurs during his encounters with Yorozu and, later, after Gojo's fall. There is talk of "love" and of how the strongest is the one who must teach others what love is. For Sukuna, love is not affection or care; it is recognition.

He "loves" his opponents to the degree that they manage to entertain him. His way of giving affection is to give them a dignified death, a death that proves that, for a brief instant, they were capable of reflecting a fraction of his light. It is a predatory love. Like a lion that respects the prey that runs faster, Sukuna recognizes the worth of those who challenge him, but that does not stop him from devouring them.

This perspective shows us that Sukuna is not a nihilist. He values strength, technique, and will. What he despises is the weakness that disguises itself as morality. For him, the only sin is to be boring or to limit oneself out of fear of the judgment of others.

---

### VI. The Legacy of the Heian Era in the Present

As the manga advances toward its climax, we see a Sukuna who has transcended even his own limits. His battle against the entire Tokyo sorcery school is not a struggle for survival, it is a final banquet. Each time he seems to be against the ropes, Sukuna reveals a new layer of his understanding of cursed energy.

He is the reminder that sorcery, at its root, is an individualistic and egotistical act. While the protagonists try to win through coordinated strategy and mutual sacrifice, Sukuna wins because his "self" is denser and heavier than the combined will of all his enemies.

There is no possible redemption for Sukuna because he does not believe he has done anything wrong. There is no "peace plan" behind his actions. If Sukuna wins, the world will simply go on existing under his whim until he grows bored and decides to turn out the lights. He is the ultimate representation of chaos that needs no justification.

---

### Conclusion: The Throne No One Can Occupy

Ryomen Sukuna remains a pillar of Gege Akutami's narrative because he is honest. He is a villain who does not lie about his intentions nor seek sympathy. He is the embodiment of the idea that perfection is solitary and that absolute power corrupts, not because it makes you "evil," but because it makes you "alien."

He is the mirror in which the insecurities of all the other characters are reflected. Before Sukuna, everyone must ask themselves: "What am I when everything I love is taken from me?" Sukuna already has the answer for himself: he is the cut, he is the fire, he is the hunger. And as long as there is something to cut or something to burn, the King of Curses will remain seated upon his throne of bones, awaiting the next dish of a banquet that never ends.

In a genre that often fears to let evil simply be evil, Sukuna is a breath of fresh and terrifying air. He is the proof that, sometimes, the monster has no mask to remove; beneath the skin, there are only more teeth.$grulla$, $grulla$Ryomen Sukuna: The Empty Throne of Malevolent Perfection$grulla$),
  ('cmnn879l7001pcndefnwzevv9', $grulla$One of the main themes in Kimetsu no Yaiba is the bond of family. This is highlighted primarily by showing the bond between Tanjiro and his sister Nezuko. His determination and perseverance show just how far he is willing to go to protect a loved one.

However, the series also shows that it is not only humans who desire a family bond, but demons as well. The Spider Family, who lived on Mount Natagumo, was one of the demonic families shown in the series, a family that was created by a lower-ranked Kizuki, Rui, our topic for today.

Rui was once a human boy who was born weak and frail, and spent most of his life trapped in his home, cared for by his parents. Rui was desperate to be a normal child, and he got the chance when he met Muzan, who offered to give him strength and power like no other. Rui was then turned into a demon with spider-like demonic abilities, but like all demons, he needed to eat humans to survive, and he ended up killing people. Once, when his parents discovered the body of a dead man, they grew afraid and believed that killing Rui was the way to stop all the murders, but before his father could attack him with a knife, Rui woke up and ended up killing them both. Shocked by the fact that his own parents were willing to kill him.

As his parents lay dying, Rui heard the final words spoken by his mother, saying that she was sorry she could not give him a better life and a healthy body. Rui then remembered the last words his father said as he raised the knife to kill him, that he should not worry because they were going to kill themselves right after, so that the three of them could live together peacefully in the afterlife. Rui then understood that this was an act of love and not of ill intent, but the realization came too late. Traumatized by his actions, Rui deeply longed for a family once again. As the years passed, Rui became a powerful demon, so powerful that Muzan gave him a large dose of his blood so that Rui could grow even stronger.

Muzan favored Rui so much that he gave him permission to create a family of his own to fill the void of his absent family. Thus began the beginnings of the Spider Family. Rui began to seek out demons, offering them protection from the Demon Slayers, but in exchange, they had to join his family. If they accepted, Rui would kill the Demon Slayers pursuing them and then take the demon to his home, where he would start a welcoming ceremony by making them drink a drop of Muzan's blood, which made them stronger. Then, Rui would transform them so that they had appearances similar to his own and assign roles such as father, mother, brother, or sister. In this way, Rui positioned himself as the younger brother even though he was clearly the strongest and the leader of the family.

The interesting thing about this tendency of Rui's is that it made him weaker. The fact that he shared Muzan's blood meant that he was not as powerful as he should have been, and this limited him to being a mere lower moon. It is possible that if Rui had consumed the blood by himself, and had set aside his desire to have a family, he would have managed to become an upper moon.

Of course, Rui does not only have his family as part of his combat power, but he also possesses powerful techniques based on:

His Blood Demon Art: Thread Manipulation

Rui's Blood Demon Art allows him to create thin threads indistinguishable from silk from his own flesh and manipulate them at will. Normally, he extends the threads from his fingers like a puppeteer. Due to the durability of his own body, the threads Rui manipulates are extremely tough and sharp, capable of cutting as well as Nichirin Swords and blocking attacks from the latter as well. Rui can further increase their strength and durability by infusing his blood through them, giving them a blood-red color.

Rui displayed terrifying skill in using his threads for combat purposes, making use of the environment to launch an avalanche of cutting attacks or to manifest inescapable web techniques to trap and cut his opponents to pieces. These are the named techniques that Rui showed us:

Cutting Thread Cage: As its name indicates, with this technique Rui creates a kind of cage like a spider web, which he uses to surround his opponent and eventually cut them from all sides. Although powerful in the sense that it is hard to escape from, it is not Rui's fastest technique, and the threads are not the toughest, so an opponent can quickly dodge or cut the threads to escape.

Murderous Eye Basket: Similar to the previous technique, this technique consists of surrounding his opponent with threads to then shrink them and cut the opponent, the difference seeming to lie in the way it is used, doing a childish cat's cradle game with the hands, and it is used against a previously incapacitated opponent.

Cutting Thread Rotation: This is Rui's most powerful technique, with which he uses control of his threads to make an intense rotation of them and concentrate them into a single wave of attack that covers a fairly extensive area. Unlike his other techniques, the speed of this one, mixed with the concentration of Rui's flesh in the threads, makes it extremely powerful, and it could surely finish off any slayer who was struck head-on by it.

Despite Rui not being an upper moon, and appearing in only part of the first season of Kimetsu, his themes are more interesting than even some of the upper Kizuki, and he is the first real enemy we see in the series, giving him great value for Tanjiro's growth. Additionally, Rui is presented as a powerful character who served to demonstrate the true power of the Hashira, especially Giyu, serving a role pointing toward the future of where our protagonist could one day reach, and for this we should give this little white spider the respect it deserves.$grulla$, $grulla$Rui$grulla$),
  ('cmnn879cd001ncndeq8zxyxfw', $grulla$What's interesting about cursed techniques in Jujutsu Kaisen as a magic system is the versatility it gives Akutami to create a wide variety of techniques with diverse uses and weaknesses. We have everything from basic abilities that let you hit harder, to abilities that manipulate space and probability to give you an advantage. However, this kind of system always lends itself to some slightly ridiculous abilities, which, when used well, can be just as powerful as the traditional ones. And there's no better example of this than our topic for today, Reggie Star and his technique based on discount coupons.

Reggie, like many others, is an ancient sorcerer reincarnated by Kenjaku to take part in the Culling Games. Although not much is known about him before his reincarnation, he is an important point of conflict specifically for Megumi, and he leads a group of antagonistic sorcerers who seek to get ahead in the Games no matter what, regardless of the means they have to use.

Reggie is an intelligent person with a playful attitude. He quickly adapted to the violence and cruelty of the Games, focusing solely on gathering strong allies while eliminating the weak or anyone who opposed him. Reggie used Remi, a cute girl, to lure in potential allies or targets in order to gain points. He claimed he would never kill her for points and then immediately treated her as completely disposable in battle the next moment, showing what he truly thinks of those who are no longer of use to him.

Reggie's callous attitude extends to his other allies as well. The associates he sought to gather were merely tools he could use to ensure his own progression in the Game. When Chizuru Hari died, Reggie was ashamed that his teammate had been killed without even using his cursed technique. He only wished to avenge Hari to make up for the points lost.

Although Reggie wanted to find allies, it's clear that he enjoys conflict and would discard anyone he deemed unworthy. Willing to engage in a fight, Reggie acknowledges his opponent's strength while remaining supremely confident in himself. This is demonstrated when, after seeing Megumi hold back, Reggie warned the young sorcerer to fight in earnest and to kill, otherwise he would end up dead.

In terms of power level, Reggie is a powerful jujutsu sorcerer whose skill earned the respect of his group of players in the Culling Games, most of whom were strong fighters in their own right. He held his own against Megumi and pushed the young sorcerer to the limit in a battle of jujutsu and deception.

Reggie overcame the Divine Dog, Totality, one of Megumi's most powerful shikigami. Megumi wanted the Divine Dog to take him down in a non-lethal manner, but Reggie drove kitchen knives into its mouth. While fighting alongside Hazenoki to ambush Megumi, Reggie summoned gas to amplify his partner's explosions. After wearing Megumi down, Reggie used a receipt for a day at the spa to rejuvenate himself and pursued him using flying drones and a motorcycle. He outmatched Megumi with his strange combination of martial arts and recreated projectiles.

Even when faced with a domain, Reggie was well prepared with an anti-domain technique. When his barrier failed to protect him, Reggie was still able to withstand the attack of Megumi's incomplete domain. Reggie's strategic mindset and physical endurance were what allowed him to survive and eventually use the domain's conditions against it.

Reggie's preferred form of combat is an unorthodox mix of a random variety of recreated objects and effective martial arts. This combination overwhelmed Megumi, where Reggie knocked him to the ground with a front kick after wounding him with a knife hidden inside a radish.

Even without the use of his cursed technique, Reggie was able to overcome Megumi with pure martial arts. Megumi was forced to acknowledge Reggie's skills and was heavily pressured despite using a cursed tool. Reggie confidently threw fast, powerful combinations of punches and kicks, enhanced by his great physical prowess at an expert level. He was skilled enough to completely outmatch Megumi in both hand-to-hand combat exchanges during their fight.

However, what makes Reggie truly interesting is his innate cursed technique: Contractual Re-Creation.

With this technique, Reggie can burn a contract of any kind, such as a discount coupon, with cursed energy. By doing this, he can recreate whatever was written on it and make it a reality. This isn't limited to physical objects, since, as I mentioned, he was able to burn a spa coupon to obtain its healing effects. The recreated objects can be commanded like shikigami, but once they fulfill their order, they disappear.

Reggie uses his technique creatively, keeping an armor of hundreds of coupons around his body that he skillfully employs for various situations. Reggie uses them both in a straightforward and a supporting manner, creating flying knives or gas to amplify explosions, as well as using drones to pursue his opponent, or vehicles to deal great damage over a wide area, which makes him a fairly versatile sorcerer.

Unfortunately, the Contractual Re-Creation technique has a pretty obvious weakness: water. Since the coupons are made of paper, destroying them with water is the easiest way to prevent Reggie from being able to use them en masse. Of course, the best example of this is the way Megumi was able to use water to trap Reggie and prevent his barrage of objects.

In addition to this, Reggie can use an anti-domain technique that is considered the predecessor of the Simple Domain, called the empty wicker basket. This esoteric technique creates a basket-shaped barrier that neutralizes the barrier of domain expansions and prevents their guaranteed-hit effect. However, against incomplete domains like Megumi's, he runs the risk that the objects or physical creatures generated by the domain could reach him, since they aren't considered a guaranteed hit. Likewise, this technique must be maintained with the user's body in a specific position, leaving him basically paralyzed in a defensive stance.

Reggie's most prominent asset is his analytical mind and his cunning talent for subterfuge. He has a gift for deception and is a strategic fighter who seeks to stay one step ahead of his opponents. Reggie is an analyst who is aware of his situation and seeks to gain an advantage by any means possible. During the early stages of the Culling Games, Reggie theorized that he couldn't take the event at face value. He predicted that Kenjaku would drop a metaphorical bomb on the game after only the strongest players remained. To prepare for this situation, Reggie focused on gathering allies and points. He used Remi to bring players to him where he could assess their abilities. The weak players were eliminated while Reggie tried to recruit powerful sorcerers like Megumi.

As you can see, although Reggie and his Re-Creation are relatively weak when compared to the pinnacle of sorcery, it's the creativity they bring to his way of fighting that makes them interesting. In fact, his fight with Megumi is one of my favorites from this arc, and this makes Reggie Star a fairly memorable character in my eyes.$grulla$, $grulla$Reggie$grulla$),
  ('cmnn8793p001lcndelk22z3we', $grulla$There are many strange creatures in the world of Jujutsu Kaisen. After all, in a world where all kinds of Cursed Spirits roam the earth so freely, seeing one or two talking animals is simply part of the routine. The same can be said about Jujutsu Sorcerers, because they too come in all kinds of shapes and sizes.

The overwhelming majority of Jujutsu Sorcerers are human, but some of them certainly seem to be far removed from what you would consider normal. Mechamaru and Panda are excellent examples of this. Mechamaru is actually a Cursed Puppet controlled by Kokichi Muta from afar. But Panda is different, so who or what is he?

We are introduced to Panda when Yuji enters the Tokyo Jujutsu academy. Panda is one of Yuji's senior classmates at that time, along with Maki Zen'in, Toge Inumaki, and Yuta Okkotsu, who was absent during the first season. Needless to say, Yuji was bewildered when he first saw Panda. But since there are still many things he doesn't know about the Jujutsu world, Yuji simply takes it as one of those mysterious things he has to accept.

Panda has an incredibly optimistic and positive personality, which makes everyone who knows him feel comfortable talking and spending time with him. As a second-year student, Panda can be considered a skilled Jujutsu sorcerer. However, unlike Inumaki, who uses a specific type of cursed technique, or Maki, who fights using cursed tools, Panda is more of a fighter who uses his incredible strength and physical power in close-quarters combat, without relying on a particular cursed technique, whether innate or inherited.

In fact, Panda's main ability is more of a physical characteristic of his construction.

Both Panda and Mechamaru are considered Cursed Corpses, that is, inanimate objects that move in a particular way. However, unlike Mechamaru, who is simply a Cursed Corpse controlled by a Jujutsu Sorcerer from afar, Panda actually belongs to a category known as Abrupt Mutation Cursed Corpse.

There are no Jujutsu sorcerers controlling how he moves and what he says from afar. Panda is a completely independent and conscious Cursed Corpse. Not only that, but Panda can also generate cursed energy just like regular Jujutsu Sorcerers, which is something unheard of in the Jujutsu world.

Panda was created by the principal of the Tokyo jujutsu school, Masamichi Yaga. Yaga is the foremost expert in the Jujutsu puppetry technique, and Panda is his masterpiece. Unlike other Cursed Corpses, which usually have only one core, Panda has three different cores in his body. That is what allows him to transform into a different attack mode. Since a core is the heart of a Cursed Corpse, Panda has the ability to change the location of his cores to better protect himself.

This is why Panda has proven capable of changing his appearance on numerous occasions. His normal panda appearance is actually his default and most balanced mode. He can transform into a gorilla mode whenever he wishes, changing his appearance to resemble an enormous gorilla. Not only that, but this mode also exponentially increases his strength. In this mode, Panda can send Mechamaru flying with a single blow, and his Drum Beat is extremely powerful and can deal damage even if the opponent blocks, since the shockwaves generated by his strikes affect the internal body of whoever blocks. Panda says that the gorilla soul is the soul of his older brother, giving a certain level of personality to his technique.

On the other hand, Panda can switch to the soul of his younger sister and take on her triceratops form, in which he changes into a two-legged dinosaur form with a triceratops head. In this form Panda takes on a feminine appearance, and his personality seems to change as well, becoming more bashful and aggressive toward whoever looks at him. Unfortunately we have not seen whether this form has special techniques, but it will surely be a faster form with a powerful charge that will seek to finish off the opponent with a single blow, though it must have lower stamina and will tire quickly.

Although Panda is unusual given his level of power and his ability to generate cursed energy, there are quite a few other Cursed Corpses like him, and all of them are created by Masamichi Yaga. After creating Panda, Yaga began to perfect his technique by creating numerous conscious Cursed Corpses of all shapes and sizes, particularly in the form of dolls. And although they are not on the same level as Panda, they are also quite strong.

Some of these dolls are used as training partners for the students of the academy, while the more powerful ones are used as combat partners or even bodyguards, as during the Shibuya Incident arc. Yaga's technique has evolved to such a high level that he can not only create a conscious Cursed Corpse with its own cursed energy and personality, but he can also inject other personalities into his dolls.

One example of this is a doll named Takeru. Like Panda, it is also a conscious Cursed Corpse. However, its personality is based on a real person, specifically Kusakabe's deceased nephew. Although the doll itself does not seem to have Takeru's actual memories, it certainly has his personality. Since the Abrupt Mutation Cursed Corpse is a highly dangerous and forbidden technique, Yaga keeps most of his creations hidden. The only one that can move freely is Panda.$grulla$, $grulla$Panda$grulla$),
  ('cmnn878up001jcndex5qmi976', $grulla$In Kimetsu no Yaiba, there are interconnections between all the characters, whether they're protagonists, antagonists, or even side characters, and the beautiful thing about the story is the sense of inherited destiny it conveys through its characters. However, there is one little girl who not only represents everything Kimetsu wants to show us, but who is, all on her own, the most important character in the entire series, not just for the side of the hunters but also for the side of the demons. Of course, she is none other than Nezuko Kamado, Tanjiro's little demon sister.

Nezuko is a crucial character in Kimetsu no Yaiba. Her mere existence is a threat to both humans and demons due to the unpredictability of her demonic powers. Although she has a miraculous control over her bloodlust, many in the Demon Slayer Corps don't believe she should exist. Nonetheless, with Tanjiro's help, Nezuko is allowed to accompany him and others in search of a cure. It's suggested that Nezuko's transition into a demon was never fully completed, hence the room for her to return. Even so, Nezuko's state allows her to transform and gradually evolve, and she does so on several occasions during battles to protect Tanjiro and the rest of her protectors.

As a recipient of the first progenitor's blood, Nezuko was granted demonic powers without remaining permanently in that state. For some inexplicable reason, she developed an unprecedented resistance to human blood and sunlight. However, it seems that most of her resistance comes from her strong sense of protecting Tanjiro. Her brother is mainly there to calm her down whenever she's on the verge of losing control. What we've witnessed since the first season is Nezuko's "dormant" or "hybrid" transformation, where most of her humanity is active. But in the second season, Nezuko finally awakened to her true demonic form, the "Awakened" form. This form is considered the maximum level Nezuko can reach in her demonic powers so far, when she enters an unrestrained state, leaving all of her humanity behind in the process. Her Awakened form is different because the transformation is more complete, making her even more powerful and highly aggressive.

Despite not being a member of the Twelve Kizuki, Nezuko is a very powerful demon. Her most outstanding trait is her extraordinary growth rate, due to the large amount of blood she received from Muzan Kibutsuji when he turned her into a demon. This has been demonstrated in many battles where she was able to defeat her enemies despite being overwhelmed by them at first. She has been shown to defeat her enemies by increasing her own physical capabilities, enhancing her regeneration, or developing her own Blood Demon Art in critical situations.

Nezuko has demonstrated great skill and prowess in combat, surpassing the Temple Demon, the Swamp Demon, and Susamaru. Later on, her power increased even further to the point where she could face members of the Twelve Kizuki, such as Daki, whom she managed to defeat easily despite not initially being a match for her, and Hantengu's clones, with whom she was able to fight on equal terms.

Nezuko has several unique characteristics that set her apart from all other demons. The most notable is that Nezuko can continuously restore her power without consuming human blood, as any other demon would need to do. Instead, she recovers her strength only through sleep, although she would have to spend a long time sleeping in order to recover and regain her power. In addition, Nezuko has an extraordinary growth rate, as has been shown several times when she becomes stronger without any training or consumption of humans. This ability is shown even in the middle of battle and with great increases in power.

Nezuko has the ability to enter a berserker state where she becomes more demonic in appearance, transforming into an adult version of herself with vine-like tattoos surrounding her body and a single horn protruding from the right side of her forehead. Nezuko's physical capabilities in this state increase drastically to the point where she could sever Daki's limbs by stomping on them and kick her from extremely far distances, destroying multiple buildings in the process. Her regenerative abilities also become equal to those of the Upper Ranks of the Twelve Kizuki. When she first awakened this ability in her fight with Daki, she became frenzied in battle, lost her usual restraint toward human blood, and only returned to normal when Tanjiro sang her a lullaby. Over time, she was able to transform into her Advanced Demon Form while maintaining her usual composure and avoiding feeding on or attacking humans.

We can't forget the fact that, like all demons, Nezuko was initially vulnerable to sunlight, and her body would completely disintegrate if exposed to it. As a result, she could only go out at night or in areas with little sunlight. However, in an event that completely changed the order of the war between hunters and demons, during her battle with Hantengu, she suddenly managed to develop immunity to sunlight, which allowed her to be active regardless of whether she was in the sun or not, and earned her the title of "The Chosen Demon."

All of this makes Nezuko completely unique compared to the rest of the demons created by Muzan, and it's what makes her the key piece for ending the series' conflict. However, we can't overlook her special ability.

Blood Demon Art: Exploding Blood

Nezuko's Blood Demon Art allows her to ignite her blood in pink-colored flames at will. Her flames have a special property that makes them harmful only to demons, objects belonging to demons, and the Blood Demon Arts of other demons, while being completely harmless to humans and other objects. These flames can hinder natural demonic regeneration, as was shown when Daki's burns took much longer to heal than traditional wounds. This technique was also able to neutralize Gyutaro's poison to save Inosuke and Tengen. Her flames also have the ability to temporarily turn nichirin swords a glowing red, increasing the strength of the attacks inflicted by them. This technique, mixed with the hunters' breathing styles, can be a weaker replacement for the red nichirin swords needed to finish off the demon king, and it seems specially designed to finish off the kizuki. However, this Blood Demon Art doesn't come without drawbacks, since because Nezuko doesn't consume human blood and depends on the rest of sleep, extended use of her technique causes her to become fatigued quickly, to the point of falling asleep.

In addition to her blood art, Nezuko has shown in her Advanced Demon Form that she has control over the viscosity of her own blood. When her limbs and head were severed and she was about to be attacked by Daki, Nezuko managed to control her limbs and head by coagulating and solidifying the blood gushing from them before the streams could break. She was able to command her limbs to grab and stop Daki's bands, and even though she did so with floating, severed limbs connected by blood, she was able to do it with such force that the bands came to a dead stop. She was then able to bring all her limbs together through those streams of blood, allowing her body to regenerate.

In conclusion, although Nezuko is clearly a relatively weak demon when it comes to the higher tiers of power on the demons' side, her particular abilities make her the key piece for the resolution and evolution not only of the plot but of the main characters on both sides in Kimetsu no Yaiba. Her blood and her very being are both the main motivator for Tanjiro and Muzan and the mechanism by which there exists a hope for stopping the demons, as well as the necessary complement for creating the perfect demon, making her, in my opinion, one of the most interesting characters in the entire work.

