 - Mai / Yorozu
---

Cursed techniques in Jujutsu Kaisen have always been an expression of their author's imagination, a way of giving different and creative powers to his characters, but some techniques are more creative than others, and none represents this concept more than the innate cursed technique of not one but two characters in the series, Mai and Yorozu, who share the difficult-to-use technique of Construction.

Construction, as its name implies, allows the user to conjure an object out of nothing. Unlike objects created inside a domain, anything constructed will remain even after the technique is finished. However, this uses a large amount of cursed energy inefficiently, which can cause a strong adverse reaction in the user's body.

Mai

Mai is Mai's twin, whom we meet briefly during the competition between the Jujutsu schools of Tokyo and Kyoto,

Like her twin sister, Mai was mistreated by the Zenin clan while growing up, simply for being a girl with little talent for jujutsu. Mai was content to live under their control as a servant and preferred doing household chores rather than fighting. Maki, on the other hand, preferred to defy the clan and work as a sorcerer. The repercussions of Maki's rebellion forced Mai to study to become a jujutsu sorcerer. Because of this, Mai detests the grotesque work of exorcising curses and resents Maki for essentially throwing them both into that life.

Mai developed the Construction technique and hid it from her twin sister while they were growing up. She uses a revolver in battle, so after firing six shots at Maki, it seemed she had run out of bullets. However, Construction allowed her to create and load another bullet charged with cursed energy into her revolver. This surprise attack was meant to catch her opponent off guard and end the fight.

Mai's limit is one bullet per day, but this drained the little cursed energy she possessed, resulting in physical consequences such as a nosebleed. After being cut down by her own father, Mai decided to use Construction to give her sister Maki a fighting chance. Mai was aware that the repercussions would kill her, but she seized that opportunity to take all the cursed energy between the twins. Mai sacrificed her life to give Maki a body of steel that escaped cursed energy, using Construction to create a great sword that symbolizes the bond between the two.

Sadly, Mai is more of a vehicle to empower Maki and doesn't have great feats or much to mention when it comes to Construction. For that, we have to talk about the other exponent of the technique.

Yorozu

Yorozu is one of the sorcerers reincarnated during Kenjaku's Culling Game, who took over the body of Tsumiki Fushiguro in her new life. In the Heian era, Yorozu was considered an extremely talented sorcerer, even recognized by the powerful Fujiwara clan. Her obsession with Sukuna is everything to her, and it's clear she would do anything to be with him, even going so far as to propose defeating him in battle if he promises to marry her.

As with Mai, Yorozu's innate technique allows her to create any matter using her cursed energy, as long as she has some knowledge and information about the matter she wishes to create. This lets her make creations that combine the properties of several different elements and materials.

Unfortunately, the cursed energy efficiency of her technique is severely lacking, even though her own cursed energy output is on par with the strongest fighters of the Heian period. This obviously causes great frustration in Yorozu, who dedicated her life to tirelessly researching a way to solve this problem.

Eventually, Yorozu slowly began to glimpse a solution to her technique's weakness. Realizing the energy efficiency of an insect's body, Yorozu came to believe that creating armor incorporating the physical aspects of various insects would largely solve Construction's energy inefficiency. This allows her to fight on the same level as, and even surpass, some of the most powerful jujutsu sorcerers of the Heian period, earning the recognition of the Fujiwara clan.

Using Construction, Yorozu can create more than mere bullets like Mai. One example of this is her insect wings, which allow her to fly at high speeds, or her liquid metal, which she uses as her main combat tool. This liquid metal can change its volume at will, and its stable physical characteristics allow it to take whatever form Yorozu requires for combat by manipulating it with cursed energy.

Yorozu can also create insect armor with the liquid metal. This is the solution to the inefficiency I mentioned earlier; Yorozu considers an insect's shell to be the ultimate armor and the ideal subject for Construction. This greatly enhances her strength, speed, and endurance, improving all her close-quarters combat abilities. It also allows her to increase her skill in mid-range combat by continuing to control liquid metal outside the armor, attacking from multiple fronts.

All of this shows us that Yorozu's control over Construction is exceptionally proficient. Her greatest achievement was even being able to create a perfect sphere, a feat considered impossible. A true sphere has no contact area and generates infinite pressure as a result, making it untouchable. It moves toward Yorozu's target at a moderate speed and becomes an obstacle in combat that her opponent must avoid at all costs or be destroyed, giving them an additional complication in fighting her.

Of course, we can't overlook that Yorozu's techniques don't stop at her mere innate technique; she is skilled enough to have her own domain expansion.

Domain Expansion: Triple Affliction

The setting of this Domain Expansion takes the form of an empty space with several oversized organic structures floating in it, resembling the disembodied brains and ventral nerve cords of insects. The domain's sure-hit effect applies to the objects constructed by the user, and by applying this effect to her true sphere, Yorozu can basically destroy the opponent instantly if they are caught in her domain.

What's interesting about Construction in the context of Jujutsu Kaisen is that, despite seeming like an extremely powerful technique, it's much more difficult to use than it appears, and it requires creativity, effort, and additional study to be as effective as the techniques of the other characters. Both Mai and Yorozu showed us different levels of Construction, and I'm grateful to both of them for giving us one of the best interpretations of this type of technique in any anime or manga series.

Tell me in the comments, what other cursed technique would you like to see explained? I'd love to hear your opinion. Also, if you liked this video and want to see others like it, don't hesitate to subscribe, and give the video a like; it helps me grow the channel a lot.

Take a look at this perfect sphere, it's the culmination of all my effort. Hey, but what do I know, I'm just a crane that comments.$grulla$, $grulla$Mai & Yorozu$grulla$),
  ('cmnn877m70019cndevlkoqsf4', $grulla$No one would blame you if, when you watch Hunter x Hunter, you focus on the strongest and most complex characters in the series, if Gon, or Killua, or Kurapika, or even Hisoka or Chrollo are your favorites. However, there is another character in the main cast who, although he is the one with the least screen time, has profound effects on the personalities of his companions and on the story itself whenever he finally deigns to appear, and whether you like his personality or not, he is in my opinion the best example of an effective support character in this story. Of course, I am talking about our favorite greedy doctor, Leorio Paradinight.

Leorio is initially presented as a very self-centered narcissist who places great emphasis on material wealth. However, despite his claims that he is only after money, he eventually reveals to Kurapika that his dream is to become a doctor in order to help the poor. He believes that all things in the world (lives, dreams, etc.) can be bought and that becoming a Hunter will provide him with the funds necessary for his medical education. Due to his first confrontation with Kurapika, as well as the test on the way to the navigator's cabin, it seems that he is sensitive toward those who do not take him seriously or treat him with disrespect. His true priorities seem to be his friends first, then his dream of becoming a great doctor, and after that everything else.

Leorio is not someone who backs down when faced with overwhelming odds in a battle. He is a loyal and reliable ally who greatly values the bonds of friendship, and he acts as the 'big brother' of the group. He often provides the comic relief in the story; Killua sometimes teases him about his comparatively older age, even though he swears his appearance is that of a mere teenager. His impulsive and bold nature has sometimes caused more problems for the people around him. Another ability he has is his capacity to "speak plainly" in many situations. You could say that his closest relationship in the group is with Kurapika, since they have spent most of the time together.

An interesting detail is that, at the end of the Yorknew City arc, Melody states that he has "the kindest heartbeat in the city," affirming that "it is warm and gentle" and that he would make a better doctor than Hunter.

To understand Leorio as a character it is important to understand his past. Leorio once lost a close friend, a boy named Pietro, to a debilitating illness. Leorio feels deeply regretful for not having been able to save his friend, since the illness was completely curable but required a surgery that he could not afford. Therefore, he aspires to become a doctor, one who not only cures the sick of their illnesses but also works pro bono for people who cannot afford it. In this sense, his seemingly superficial reason for joining the Hunter Exams in pursuit of great wealth takes on a more noble justification: the money he earns is used not only to fund his medical studies, but also to pay for medicine and other miscellaneous expenses when treating those who cannot afford it.

In terms of abilities and power level, you could say that Leorio's power is centered more on his influence and empathy than on combat abilities. He has shown us how he is capable of earning the trust of even the strongest, and how he is capable of mobilizing the masses. His position as a member of the Zodiacs is not because of how strong he is, but because of how much his fellow Hunters trust him. Of course, that position gives him certain advantages and authorities, allowing him to give orders even if his physical or Nen power does not back him up.

Leorio's actual combat abilities are unknown. During the Hunter Exam, he was able to survive being struck by one of Hisoka's cards, although he was still injured, and Netero declared that his combat prowess was superior to Bodoro's. He left a strong enough impression on Hisoka to be considered an opponent worth giving the chance to "ripen." Despite being moderately observant, Leorio's temper often leads him to act impulsively, and we have not actually seen him do more than land a fairly satisfying punch on Ging using his Nen ability and catching him off guard, although it is clear that Ging let himself be hit in order to make Leorio look good.

As a professional Hunter and Nen user, Leorio has above-average perception, strength, speed, and reflexes, and even among average Hunters he could be considered someone slightly skilled; it is only when we compare him to his three other protagonist companions that he begins to look weak. Leorio is also a specialist in the use of knives and can throw them with enough force to pierce through stone pillars.

Of course, his medical knowledge is quite impressive thanks to his studies. It has been said that his first-aid skills are the best there are, and he is capable of identifying when people are faking unconsciousness just by examining them.

In terms of his Nen, Leorio is an Emitter who leans toward Enhancement. Because he postponed his training in order to apply to university, by the time he reunited with Gon and Killua in Yorknew City, he could only use Ten and was unaware of the existence of other techniques. It is possible that he learned Zetsu in a single day, since he managed to sneak up on Kurapika. However, during the Election of the 13th Chairman, it was shown that Leorio had improved greatly, developing at least one Nen ability. According to Ging, he might also possess another ability that earned him the praise of one of the most skilled Nen users in the world. Ging is of the opinion that Leorio's Nen ability was strongly influenced by his studies in medicine.

His Hatsu is the Remote Punch. After striking an object in his proximity, Leorio emits his aura in a line that travels along a surface from the point of impact to a desired location. A wormhole-like circle is generated, from which a fist emerges that strikes the target with an upward hook, extending far beyond the length of a normal arm. Ging, who imitated this technique, demonstrated that multiple blows can be emitted by striking a surface several times, although it is unknown whether Leorio can do the same.

It is an interesting ability with great potential for surprise attacks or even support to help his companions, and this is without mentioning its possible medical use, perhaps being usable to perform a non-invasive surgery on a patient, and maybe even to cure illnesses with surgeries that were previously impossible. This is clearly what Leorio seeks with his technique, even if unconsciously, thanks to his great motivation to save others.

As you can see, Leorio is much more than a mediocre fighter. He is the one who cares the most about his friends, and the only one in the main group who is truly altruistic in his motivations and actions. His attitudes and actions have not gone unnoticed and have earned him praise not only from Ging but from the rest of the Zodiacs, and he has become, almost by accident, a key figure in the world of Hunters.$grulla$, $grulla$Leorio$grulla$),
  ('cmnn877dd0017cndeofhwjm10', $grulla$In Jujutsu Kaisen we always center the conversation on cursed techniques. The broken abilities that define the power of most characters, and that give versatility and creativity to Akutami's world. The exceptions to this rule are few, and most of them focus on the completely opposite side, or on heavenly restrictions that entirely remove the possibility of using techniques with cursed energy in exchange for powerful physical abilities, as with Toji and Maki. However, there is a third option that we know of in very few characters, but through which it is possible to reach a great level of power and be a fairly strong sorcerer. This is through the mastery of martial skills mixed with specialization in a type of technique that any sorcerer can learn, the Simple Domain, or more specifically the New Shadow Style mastered by Atsuya Kusakabe.

Technically, Kusakabe is a teacher at the Tokyo Jujutsu High, but it doesn't seem like his role is an important part of his character, since Kusakabe is mainly characterized by being a fearful person who is focused on his own self-preservation as his top priority. He is also willing to be deceptive to save his own skin, as was shown during the Shibuya Incident, where he repeatedly lied to Panda to keep him close for safety, while steering him away from where Gojo was sealed in order to avoid facing special grade curses. This shows that he isn't the most responsible person in the world, and he tends to worry more about himself than about his students or colleagues.

However, he also has a brave side, as was seen when he protected Miwa from Kenjaku's Uzumaki, which also shows that he is capable of setting aside his selfishness and having a heroic side as a teacher.

Kusakabe is not one of the central characters of Jujutsu Kaisen, and very little is really known about him beyond his abilities and techniques. He is the uncle of Takaba, a dead child whose personality now inhabits one of Yaga's cursed corpses, and we know that he has a younger sister whom he cares about quite a bit, but this doesn't give us much material to focus on.

Kusakabe's main point of interest is his peculiarity of being a first grade sorcerer despite not being able to use cursed techniques. This particular level of power warrants taking a closer look at him.

Despite not possessing an innate technique, Kusakabe is a respected grade 1 sorcerer and a master swordsman of the New Shadow Style. Mei Mei considered Kusakabe to be the only sorcerer of his grade who reached that rank without an innate technique. According to her, according to Kento Nanami and Satoru Gojo, Kusakabe is the strongest grade 1 sorcerer. Satoru specified that his statement might not be accurate if the sorcerers of the Three Great Families were taken into account.

Despite such praise, Kusakabe openly admits on several occasions that he has no chance of defeating a special grade curse and avoids them at all costs. However, he is completely certain that he can defeat other adversaries such as the curse users Toshihisa Negi and Manami Suda, whom he considers to be below his level.

While several jujutsu sorcerers in training were struggling to obtain Kenjaku's Prison Realm, Kusakabe stepped in just in time to save the lives of all of his allies. Even Kenjaku commented on Kusakabe's knowledge of the New Shadow Style, seemingly as a sign of respect for his skill.

Kusakabe's swordsmanship is his main weapon in battle, relying heavily on his physical prowess. In combination with the swordsmanship techniques of the New Shadow Style, he has demonstrated a high proficiency in handling his sword. Using the Battō style, Kusakabe quickly dispatched three curse user henchmen in an instant.

As a grade 1 sorcerer, Kusakabe possesses respectable levels of cursed energy. To compensate for his lack of an innate technique, Kusakabe has mastered the New Shadow Style. This requires finely controlled applications of cursed energy, such as casting a Simple Domain and coating the blade of his katana with cursed energy. Kusakabe also has a sharp sense for judging the strength of his opponent, being able to recognize someone of his level versus a special grade in an instant.

Kusakabe's Simple Domain is an application of a barrier technique to coat his body or his sword and thus increase his power, restore its form, or repel other barriers such as, for example, a domain expansion.

During the peak era of jujutsu in the Heian Era, Sadatsuna Ashiya created the "domain for the weak" with the purpose of protecting his followers from curses and curse users. Binding vows were established that prohibited teaching the Simple Domain to outsiders, but other sorcerers saw the technique in action and were able to copy it for themselves, something the vows did not account for.

Created as a counter to domain expansions, the Simple Domain neutralizes the guaranteed-hit function of a domain by affecting its barrier and not the cursed technique imbued within it. However, against a proper domain expansion, the Simple Domain can only hope to buy time for its user. Powerful domains can destroy simple domains in a matter of seconds.

The barriers of the Simple Domain can be customized with different rules and binding vows to affect those who find themselves inside it, both the caster and the target.

Kusakabe's application of the Simple Domain in his swordsmanship is similar to what we have seen with Miwa but on a much higher level; it can be said that he is the greatest expert of this application. This allowed Kusakabe to protect himself from Kenjaku's Uzumaki and from Sukuna's slashes, incredibly high feats that demonstrate the fine control he has over his barriers as well as his skill and perception.

In addition to this, Kusakabe mixes the New Shadow Style with his named sword techniques to give specific effects to his Simple Domain. These are:

Iai Battō: This technique consists of covering the blade of his katana with the barrier of the Simple Domain, increasing the speed with which the sword comes out of its sheath. This makes it the fastest technique of the New Shadow Style, and it manages to catch countless opponents off guard, as they do not expect this extreme level of speed.

Iai Night Moon Sword: This stance activates a defensive Simple Domain on Kusakabe's sword. While inside the Simple Domain, Kusakabe's cursed energy output is increased while the cursed techniques that intrude upon it are slightly weakened. By incorporating an original program into the Simple Domain, Kusakabe can automatically intercept anything that enters the Simple Domain with his katana.

Blurred Moon: With this technique Kusakabe can use the Simple Domain to reform part of his katana with cursed energy in case it is destroyed; this allows him to cover one of his greatest weaknesses, the fact that he uses a normal katana that can be destroyed. Although it is important to mention that Kusakabe's use of cursed energy raises his katana to the level of a high-level cursed tool.

As you can see, just because Kusakabe can't use an innate or inherited cursed technique, it doesn't mean he is weak; on the contrary, it is easy to underestimate him, and the speed of his techniques mixed with his mastery of the New Shadow Style are capable of taking advantage of any opening in the opponent and even finishing them off in a single blow. The mere fact that Kusakabe was able to stand against Sukuna for as long as he did makes him, as his fellow teachers said, one of the strongest first grade sorcerers to ever exist, and this with the simple mastery of a barrier technique and his skills with the sword$grulla$, $grulla$Kusakabe$grulla$),
  ('cmnn8773r0015cnde1a2pm1i4', $grulla$Motivations are inseparable parts of characters. Those aspects of their past, or of their desires for the future, that move them and shape their personality are what make them who they are, and there is no more important motivator in the world of Hunter x Hunter than revenge. Revenge for your loved ones, revenge for yourself, or revenge for your clan. This powerful feeling is enough to bring out a person's potential, and in Kurapika's case, it is his entire being, what dictates his every move and even what limits and empowers his hatsu and all of his Nen abilities.

Kurapika is my favorite character in Hunter x Hunter, and his Hatsu is my favorite Nen ability in the entire series, and this is due to its complexity but also its focus toward a single objective. Kurapika is the last survivor of the Kurta clan, or the clan of the scarlet eyes, after his entire clan was hunted down for their valuable eyes. This naturally explains his character's obsession with recovering the precious relics of his fellow clansmen, and it is all he can think about most of the time.

However, this does not mean Kurapika is one-dimensional; if anything, I would dare say that the internal conflict he shows us, and his attitudes toward the different kinds of people he encounters throughout the arcs, make him one of the most complex and profound.

We first meet Kurapika in the Hunter Exam arc as an intelligent, kind, and honest boy who makes friends easily and has an incredible latent talent as a Hunter. However, even in this arc, the darkness within him suddenly begins to show whenever the subject of his eyes or his clan is touched upon, and it reveals his uncharacteristic loss of self-control when it comes to this part of his being.

Of course, in York New, Kurapika could be considered the protagonist, and it is here that we learn the extent of what this boy is capable of doing and sacrificing in order to achieve his revenge. This dark arc perfectly reflects the darkness and loneliness in Kurapika's soul, and just as the Hunter Exam arc showed us his light with touches of darkness, this arc shows the black void in his heart, but not without showing us, in his interactions with Melody and his companions, that there is light in there too. These small displays of kindness show us the other side of Kurapika that we surely forget beneath his hatred and bloodlust, and they make us wonder which side is the true one.

From this point on Kurapika becomes more mysterious; we are mostly absent from him for the rest of the arcs. However, after passing the endpoint of the anime adaptation and venturing into the manga-exclusive arcs, we return to Kurapika as protagonist, and we come to understand not only his dark and light sides, but his intelligence, his tactical skills, and the sheer versatility of his ability and Nen.

In terms of power level, Kurapika's powers increase enormously as the series progresses. Hisoka was the first to take an interest in him, classifying him as one of the "green fruits" with vast potential. Although he was weaker than Killua at first, by the Yorknew arc he had become stronger than him thanks to his Nen abilities. He is one of the few characters to have killed a member of the infamous Phantom Troupe, and a very powerful member at that, in Uvogin. His exceptional intelligence is on par with his great combat prowess and his iron will, which stems from his desire for revenge. He is also a very versatile fighter, as he has been seen wielding different weapons. In his confrontation with Uvogin, he used his chains both at range and in close-quarters combat, and he has been seen using a Bokken, knives, Shuriken, and even firearms such as pistols.

Of course, if we are going to talk about his power level, we cannot leave aside his Scarlet Eyes. When a member of the Kurta Clan becomes enraged, their eyes turn a vivid shade of red, which triggers an astonishing increase in physical strength. In this state, even as a child, Kurapika could gain the advantage in terms of speed and strength against three adults and overpower them easily. However, Kurapika admitted that when his eyes turn scarlet, he loses all restraint and rationality and becomes primal, which also happens whenever he sees a Spider. Furthermore, excessive use of his Scarlet Eyes can have serious repercussions on his health, as doing so left him incapacitated and feverish for more than a day, with Melody's Nen ability unable to bring his body temperature down. His current limit is about 3 hours, after which the pain and fatigue become too intense and he passes out for three times as long. Kurapika also speculates that prolonged repeated use, or uses induced by stealing particularly powerful abilities, may cause him to reach the limit before 3 hours have passed. At some point during his Nen training, Kurapika learned to turn his eyes scarlet at will and gained the ability to control his emotions.

Kurapika is one of the most brilliant characters in the series. Because of this, he was named leader of Neon's bodyguards after Dalzollene's death. He outmaneuvered minds on the level of Chrollo with carefully planned strategies, and his predictions have rarely turned out to be wrong. He also has immense knowledge on many subjects, ranging from psychology to other cultures, from history to criminology, a quality that surprised his companions when he was just a child. Due to his thirst for new knowledge, he learns quickly and has an impressive memory. Kurapika's analytical skills are so outstanding that they have led to a rumor spreading among the assassins of Muherr that he is capable of reading minds. While searching for Halkenburg in Kakin's bodyguard registry, he used the vaguest of clues to pick out the person he felt was Halkenburg, something Oito praised.

Kurapika can formulate flawless plans even in combat to fully exploit his opponent's weaknesses. His intuition is combined with his logical thinking and meticulous preparations. Although he can stay calm in desperate situations, he can barely stick to his own plan when it comes to the Phantom Troupe, to the point where he might even lose control and endanger not only himself but also his friends. On the Black Whale, he showed greater composure than before and pulled off his greatest strategic feat to date, becoming the linchpin of a stalemate, or at least an obstacle, in the succession contest with an endless series of tactics, mixing truth and lies, secrets and deliberately disclosed information. His disclosure of the existence of Nen and its categories constituted the biggest shift in the succession contest, forcing an impasse and increasing the survival odds of the lower-ranked princes.

As far as his Nen goes, Kurapika is a Conjurer, a Nen user who can create objects out of nothing according to his imagination, but he becomes a Specialist when his eyes turn scarlet. He learned Nen in very little time and is considered a highly skilled user. In terms of theoretical knowledge, he can divide Nen learners by aptitude, and he is an expert in the mechanics of Nen Limitations and Manipulation. Kurapika has Nen abilities that incorporate elements of Emission, Manipulation, and Enhancement; in addition, he has shown proficiency in Transmutation, proving to be a complete Nen user and one of the few who can access all six categories of Nen. The weapon he conjures is unique: five chains that extend from each finger of his right hand. Some of the fingers were specially designed to take revenge on the Phantom Troupe. To increase the effectiveness of his chains against them, Kurapika imposed strict Limitations on the use of his chains. Since the chains are materialized, their size and length can be controlled to a certain extent. He is able to hide his chain through In to bind his opponent without them realizing it until it is too late. Kurapika is also proficient in other branches of Nen, such as Shu, which, combined with Emperor Time, gives his chains the ability to break rocks. He has reached such a high level of skill that he can remain in a state of Ten without conscious thought.

By using a Limitation that puts his own life at risk, his abilities received a great boost. In fact, one of his chains is so strong that Uvogin, an experienced fighter, assumed it was a real chain that Kurapika was manipulating. The combination of his Limitation, the increase in ability granted by his Specialization power, and the aura boost granted by his Scarlet Eyes allowed him to close the gap in strength against a master Enhancer like Uvogin. Repeated use of his Scarlet Eyes combined with Nen takes a great toll on his mind and body, causing a high and incapacitating fever that, after Pakunoda's death, lasted several days and could not be relieved by Melody's flute.

Let's talk about each of Kurapika's chains.

Dowsing Chain:

A chain that ends with a small ball-shaped weight, which Kurapika frequently uses in combat for both offensive and defensive purposes. Its main use is as a tool for pendulum dowsing, with the ball moving according to Kurapika's objective at any given moment. As such, it is useful for investigation, since the chain can be used to determine the location of missing persons (moving in their direction) and to identify whether someone is lying (moving back and forth). If the chain's ability is used on a group, it works best if the people being questioned answer one at a time. Under normal conditions, Kurapika must be directly in front of the target for lie detection to be effective; however, when Emperor Time is active, he can also use that ability through video recordings, as long as he has met the subject before. Kurapika himself does not know how this aspect of his power works; his guess is that, through the transmission of the chain and extreme concentration, he can unconsciously detect subtle signs that someone is lying.

Chain Jail

An extremely durable chain with a hook on the end, whose sole purpose is to capture members of the Phantom Troupe and deprive them of their freedom. It forces captives into a state of Zetsu, shutting off their aura and preventing the use of Nen abilities; consequently, the only way to escape this chain is through brute force, although not even Uvogin, the physically strongest member of the Spiders, could break free from it. The chain manifests so quickly that Kurapika can completely immobilize a distant target in half a second. To create the jail, Kurapika imposed the Limitation that it can only be used on members of the Spiders, with the additional stipulation that violating this rule will result in his death.

Emperor Time

When Kurapika's eyes turn scarlet, he changes from a Conjurer to a Specialist. This ability allows him to use all types of Nen at 100% efficiency (for a Conjurer). Kurapika explains this using the terms "Level," "Strength," and "Precision": his "Levels" in the various Nen categories remain the same during Emperor Time, but his "Strength" and "Precision" for each category are raised to 100%. Thus, if Kurapika's "Level" in Conjuration was 10, his "Level" in Emission (the polar opposite aura type) would still be 4 at most, but his "Strength" and "Precision" in any Emission ability would increase from 40% to 100%, making him an even match against a Level 4 Emitter. However, the price to pay is considerable, since every second spent in this mode reduces Kurapika's lifespan by one hour.

Holy Chain

Through his cross pendant, this chain heals wounds by drawing on Enhancement-type Nen. When Kurapika is in his Specialist state, the chain can heal serious injuries, such as a fractured arm, in a matter of seconds. Apart from this it does not seem to have many other uses, but having a healing ability is extremely useful for Kurapika given the level of danger of his main mission.

Judgment Chain

Through the blade at its end, called the stake of vengeance, this chain enters a victim's body and coils around their heart. Kurapika then declares a binding rule that, if violated by the victim, causes the stake to pierce their heart and kill them. Kurapika himself has a blade around his own heart, which he used to set the limitations on the use of the Chain Jail ability. He is able to issue at least two commands per stake, and he can dissolve the chain at will, and he is certain that he would be alerted if a member of the Spiders removed it. Due to Kurapika's low affinity and mastery in Emission and Manipulation, the Judgment Chain can only be used during Emperor Time.

Stealing Chain

With a syringe-shaped end, this chain, upon piercing a target's body, extracts their aura and steals one of their Nen abilities. While their aura is being drained (a process that seems painful), the target is forced into a Zetsu-like state. Afterward, the target cannot use the stolen ability until it is returned to them. There are no conditions for stealing an ability other than piercing the target with the syringe: so far, Kurapika has stolen two abilities, one after the owner's Nen type was revealed and the general mechanics of the ability explained, and another that was about to be used without any prior knowledge. The death of the original owner does not result in Kurapika losing possession of a stolen ability.

Stealth Dolphin

By activating Emperor Time, Kurapika can summon a dolphin-like Nen beast with a syringe on each pectoral fin that is visible and audible only to him. This construct can "equip" and analyze the stolen ability, informing Kurapika of its name, functions, and conditions. Kurapika can then use the stolen ability himself or lend it to another person, including non-users, by jabbing them with the Stealing Chain. In the latter case, a listening device is conjured in that person's ear, allowing them to see the dolphin and communicate with it through telepathy. The dolphin can advise the new recipient on how to use the ability, and it will use the ability itself when ordered to by the recipient of the lent ability. When Kurapika, or someone he has lent an ability to, activates it, it is fueled by the aura that the Stealing Chain extracted from its owner, ensuring it is used with the original power.

A side effect of the Stealth Dolphin is that when it is used on a non-user, it allows them to see aura and, after the lent ability has been activated, it half-opens all of their aura nodes, essentially making them Nen users, although training is still required to control the flow of aura and prevent it from leaking.

If Kurapika equips the dolphin with a stolen ability and transfers it to another person, he can use the Stealing Chain again, but the transfer does not allow him to leave Emperor Time until he calls the dolphin back, and the stolen ability must be used in order to do so. Regardless of who controls the stolen ability, it can only be used once, after which it returns to the original user. As a drawback, as long as all stolen abilities have not been returned, Emperor Time will remain active. The dolphin will regularly notify Kurapika of how long it has been active unless it is put into standby mode, in which case it can be made to disappear. If Kurapika passes out while another person is using an ability he has lent them, that person will pass out as well.

Of course, we cannot talk about the Stealing Chain and the Stealth Dolphin without talking about Kurapika's stolen abilities, so let's go through them quickly:

Little Eye:

Kurapika stole this ability from Sayird. With it, the user throws a ball of aura at an insect or any other small, living creature, capturing it and gaining control over it. The largest creature the user can control is about the size of a hamster. The user gains knowledge of everything the manipulated animal sees or hears. For this reason, the ability is particularly useful when used on flies or mosquitoes, but since they have many natural predators, they tend to die while under the effect of the ability. Faster animals can be difficult to catch. The ability cannot be used on living beings created through aura. The controlled animal retains the user's ability to see aura. This ability seems to consume very little aura, since even a person who was not originally a Nen user could maintain it for an hour without noticeable strain. Moreover, it does not deactivate if the user passes out.

Air Blow

Kurapika stole this ability from Vincent. Little is known about it. The original user tried to activate it through his left palm to break the guard of a Nen user who was capable of stopping bullets with his aura. It seems it does not require direct contact with the target to work, and we can infer that it is a blow of air that can stun or open up an enemy's guard.

Erigeron

Lastly, Bill voluntarily allowed Kurapika to steal this ability, which dramatically accelerates the growth of living beings when the user brings their palms close to them. Its main use is to develop other people's Nen abilities, although the effects on people with little talent are quite mild.

As you can see, Kurapika's Nen abilities, like his character, are extensive and complex, which sometimes makes them a little difficult to understand. However, the objective of both is clear: to wipe out the Spiders and recover the scarlet eyes of his fellow clansmen, and although he takes it a bit to the extreme, I think we can all identify with Kurapika a little, whether in his darkest moments or his most illuminated ones.$grulla$, $grulla$Kurapika$grulla$),
  ('cmnn876uz0013cndevpenz9f5', $grulla$The special grade in Jujutsu Kaisen is reserved for the strongest of the strong, whether sorcerers or cursed spirits, and they are extremely rare and limited, giving us a sense of just how truly special they are. Sadly, among the curses, there are few in the special grade that are truly monstrous, with most of them being basically humanoids with particular traits. However, one of my favorite cursed spirits, and one that causes terror both inside and outside the world of Jujutsu Kaisen, is Kurourushi, our topic for today.

Kurourushi is a special grade cursed spirit released by Kenjaku's Cursed Spirit Manipulation during the Culling Game arc. What makes him particular is that Kurourushi participates in the games as just another player, and in fact he has some of the most interesting fights and abilities we have seen in the arc.

Kurourushi looks like what you would expect from a cockroach cursed spirit. His face, arms, and legs have the appearance of being made from a light-colored insect exoskeleton. Kurourushi is quite tall and can produce up to four human arms. He also possesses human hands and feet, and his abdomen is completely hidden by a black cloak that extends down from his head. He generally covers his wings and extremities, but they can be seen when they move.

Kurourushi's face is grotesque and perfectly reflects the alien nature of an insect like a cockroach. With six long antennae protruding from it, Kurourushi's face has eight separate sets of eyes in different places and human-like teeth behind his multi-layered jaw.

Kurourushi does not possess a distinctive ego and is instead driven entirely by his instincts as a cursed spirit. He only wants to devour humans in an attempt to satisfy his insatiable appetite. He feels disgust toward anything that gets in the way of his feeding.

When Yuta interrupted Kurourushi's meal after he awoke in a state of hunger, the cockroach curse focused solely on devouring him instead. Kurourushi even questioned why Yuta was interfering. When Yuta responded by asking why Kurourushi kills, the cockroach curse simply stated that he loved the taste of iron.

Kurourushi is one of only sixteen registered special grade cursed spirits. Humanity shares a collective fear and disdain for cockroaches, which gave rise to Kurourushi. He possesses the unique physiology of a humanoid cockroach, as well as the ability to summon and manipulate endless cockroaches reinforced by his cursed energy. In addition, Kurourushi can use cursed techniques and wield his signature cursed tool, the Putrid Life Sword, an especially dangerous weapon. At some point in the past, Kurourushi was defeated by Suguru Geto or Kenjaku and was absorbed into Cursed Spirit Manipulation. Kenjaku released Kurourushi so that the cursed spirit could compete at an elite level in the Culling Game.

Despite generally acting on the instinct to satisfy an endless appetite, Kurourushi is a relatively intelligent creature compared to most cursed spirits. Although not to the degree of the unregistered special grades like Jogo, Mahito, Hanami, or Dagon, Kurourushi can speak and communicate clearly. He understands his own status within the Culling Game and collected fifty-two points before reaching a stalemate with the most powerful players in the Sendai colony. The cockroach curse was intelligent enough to understand that Dhruv would have been an unfavorable matchup and decided to enter a state of hibernation. Kurourushi also prepared for the worst by creating offspring that would inherit his cursed energy in case he was exorcised.

In terms of power level, Kurourushi was born from the collective hatred, fear, and resentment associated with cockroaches. These negative emotions manifested special grade levels of cursed energy. Each cockroach under Kurourushi's control is imbued with his cursed energy and possesses enough strength to devour a human being as a group. Kurourushi consistently manipulates large quantities of cockroaches while also using cursed techniques, demonstrating meticulous and innate control.

Kurourushi can produce and control countless swarms of real cockroaches reinforced by his cursed energy. These man-eating cockroaches can strip all the flesh from a group of humans in a matter of seconds. This feeds Kurourushi's endless appetite and stimulates parthenogenesis. A single cockroach poses no real threat, but a full swarm can be a serious problem even for a jujutsu sorcerer.

The flesh devoured by the cursed cockroaches stimulates Kurourushi's process of parthenogenesis, granting him the ability to produce more cockroaches. In addition, Kurourushi uses this to reproduce an identical but completely new cursed spirit offspring. To preserve Kurourushi's existence, the parent's cursed energy is passed on to the child when it dies. In a way, this makes the concept of Kurourushi, rather than the creature itself, relatively immortal, as long as he has enough time to create his offspring before being exorcised.

One particular ability he shows us is his Earth Insect Trance, a cursed technique that conjures flying insect curses carrying large sacs filled with a liquid substance that is released when they are destroyed. The substance enters the target's eyes to affect their vision, giving Kurourushi time to escape, or to attack his opponent from another angle.

Of course, Kurourushi also has his iconic cursed tool.
The Putrid Life Sword is said to be an enchanted blade that mixes life and death. It is a short, thick sword, similar to a butcher's knife, with a unique shape and a grotesque design fitting for an insect to wield. Its most prominent features are six distinct firing barrels on the front of the blade that can launch short-range projectiles at its target.

Even if the sword is blocked by the opponent's weapon, it is able to fire small eggs into the enemy's flesh to infect them. Shortly after embedding themselves in the target's skin, the eggs hatch and small insect-like curses emerge from the wound. The same effect occurs if the blade cuts the target directly as well. This is what gives Kurourushi an advantage against opponents who focus on mid-range attacks like Takako Uro, whose arm he ended up cutting off with this weapon before being exorcised himself.

Kurourushi is not really one of the cursed spirits with the greatest presence in the Culling Game arc or in the Jujutsu Kaisen series, but his abilities and especially his presence as a balance to the characters of the Sendai colony are very important to the story, and he warrants discussion, despite being simply a giant cockroach with a butcher's knife.

We cannot forget that the fact that special grade curses exist who can put up a fight not only against Uro and Ryu but against Yuta himself shows us the power level of the 16 registered special grade curses, so the existence and use of Kurourushi in the story is quite relevant, and despite not being the strongest in the world, his concept and theme are very interesting for lovers of horror and character design in Jujutsu Kaisen.

Now, on the darkest night, be careful with the corners covered in shadows, because there may be a hungry creature straight out of your nightmares hiding right there.$grulla$, $grulla$Kurourushi$grulla$),
  ('cmnn876m50011cndeqs5j9o35', $grulla$There are character clichés in the world of anime that everyone knows, and one of the most prominent and beloved by many is the hooligan with a heart of gold. Those characters who look aggressive and know how to fight, yet who don't hesitate for a single second to protect the weakest people or to save someone in danger. Even in a fantastical shonen like Hunter x Hunter, we have this kind of character, but with twists that are even more unexpected, which make our character for today, Knuckle Bine, feel fresh and different, and manage to capture the attention of many of us.

True to his character archetype, despite seeming aggressive, Knuckle is very compassionate and is easily moved to tears. He gets along well with animals and feels obligated to protect the defenseless, taking care of the pets abandoned after a genocide. However, Knuckle's empathy sometimes interferes with his mission, making him a talented but troublesome member of the beast hunters, and a mismatched pair with Shoot on their mission during the Chimera Ant arc.

In the past, when Knuckle graduated from elementary school, he punched a police officer to help his friend escape, fleeing from a patrol of cars and motorcycles for a day and a night without being captured. At one point, Knuckle felt motivated to pass the Hunter exam in order to try to protect all the animals he could, and he became the apprentice of Morel, an extremely renowned hunter. An interesting fact is that even though Knuckle is a relatively new hunter, his love for protecting others has led him to wage more than 5,000 battles, an extremely high number for his age.

Despite seeming impulsive and foolish, Knuckle is one of the most strategically patient and intelligent characters in the entire series, demonstrating composure in difficult moments as well as the ability to use his powerful but hard-to-apply technique in extremely creative and effective ways.

In terms of power level, Knuckle has demonstrated considerable abilities in physical combat, being capable of fighting enemies much stronger than himself. He could have defeated Gon with just two punches if not for his kindness, which has often been said to be his greatest weakness. In fact, Killua stated that he is as strong as Kite, physically speaking, but is too soft. Because of his ability, he has adopted a hit-and-run tactic together with Shoot against other Nen users, which consists of capturing or delivering the final blow after the target's Nen is sealed. Knuckle is very versatile, being able to successfully cooperate with various Hunters who have completely different abilities and personalities. Despite being a good strategist, Knuckle is also impulsive and very emotional, which can cause him not to stick to the plan.

A curious aspect is that he is slow to start taking fights seriously, claiming he needs four or five punches to warm up.

In addition, he is very loved by animals, which, according to Ging and his son, is proof of being a good Hunter.

An interesting point is that physically Knuckle is stronger than an Enhancer like Gon, without being an Enhancer himself. He is capable of making him feel as if he were burning after one of his punches.

It is also known that Knuckle is faster than Gon. He demonstrated this by surpassing him in movement speed to the point of being able to appear behind him after landing a punch. Even after repeated battles, and despite matching him in attack speed, Gon considered his eyesight unreliable for following Knuckle and instead relied on his aura. Knuckle managed to dodge multiple attacks from Youpi while fleeing despite the latter's reach, as well as to escape his explosions twice despite being very close to the epicenter just before the detonation. He got used to Cheetu's astonishing speed and was already able to follow him with his eyes after the first exchanges, although his body was too slow to keep up with his reflexes.

Notably, Knuckle is not only fast, but also has very good stamina, being able to maintain his speed for a long time. All of this together makes Knuckle an extremely strong hunter even without using his Hatsu, perhaps even one of the most powerful we have seen, excluding of course the most extreme cases such as Hisoka, Chrollo, or Netero.

As far as his Nen is concerned, being a professional hunter and the disciple of a Single-Star Hunter, Knuckle is a highly trained Nen user. Since he managed to surpass Gon and Killua and inflict significant damage on the former despite his natural category, he also seems to be well versed in enhancement, despite it not being his main category. His abilities in this type helped him survive Gon's full-power attack without lasting injuries despite his lower aura output. Of course, Knuckle's main Nen category is conjuration, given his ability to conjure a Nen beast. He is a capable user of Ko, Ryu, Gyo, and Zetsu. In battle, he can maintain a state of Ken for 20 minutes without the slightest difficulty. He is skilled at anticipating his opponents' movements by analyzing the flow of their aura. He also excels at converting aura into numbers, which is extremely useful for his Nen ability. Thanks to his vast combat experience, he can estimate the general amount of aura an opponent possesses through physical contact, or make more precise guesses through prolonged observation, taking into account their output, stamina, and skill level.

His Hatsu is called Hakoware or Bankruptcy, and it is, in my opinion, the most interesting but complex Hatsu of all the ones we have seen.

Hakoware involves Knuckle conjuring an indestructible Nen Beast called the "Amortization Power Redirector or (A.P.R.)" onto the opponent after they have received a punch from Knuckle, emitting his aura into his opponent. A.P.R. constantly lends Knuckle's aura to whoever it is attached to, which is shown by a rising counter on their forehead. When adding interest, A.P.R. announces "It's time to add interest." As long as A.P.R. is attached, any attack made on Knuckle by his opponent returns aura to him, reducing the counter. Until all the aura lent by Knuckle is returned to him, his opponent cannot physically harm him. The reverse is also true: each of Knuckle's punches only lends more aura to his opponent, without causing damage. The stronger the attack, the more aura is lent or returned. In both cases, the person who receives the blow can still be knocked down by it, despite not suffering any damage.

A.P.R.'s interest rate is 10% of the lent aura, which accumulates every 10 seconds as long as the victim is within 50 meters of Knuckle. As the amount of lent aura (including interest) accumulates, A.P.R. also grows in size. When the aura lent by Knuckle exceeds the opponent's total remaining aura, the opponent "goes bankrupt." Therefore, it is in Knuckle's interest for his opponent to spend/waste as much aura as possible, as fast as possible (as long as that aura is not spent on Knuckle himself). The result is that the opponent's "aura balance" drops much faster until it is below the amount they owe Knuckle (shown by A.P.R.), at which point they can no longer pay their debt, and bankruptcy is established.

Bankruptcy causes A.P.R. to transform into the "Individual Ren Suppressor or (I.R.S.)," a demonic pet that follows the debtor for 30 days and forces them to be in a continuous state of Zetsu. It is worth mentioning that when Knuckle hit Shaiapouf's copy, A.P.R. attached itself to the latter's real body instead of his clone, making it useful against this type of opponent. Furthermore, Knuckle can use Hakoware on multiple targets at once, as well as track their general location at all times, regardless of distance. The ability can be removed by an Exorcist, but it heavily drains the one removing the Nen. It is also canceled if Knuckle is knocked unconscious.

Although the Nen types used by Hakoware are confusing, it is clear that it at least uses conjuration to call the Nen beast, and it is possible that it uses emission to lend his aura to the opponent. It is considered an extremely advanced and precise technique, since it not only requires Knuckle to be able to convert aura into nominal values, but the ability to inflict a state of Zetsu and prevent the user from using their Nen is extremely rare, valuable, and difficult to control.

Knuckle's personality and ability make him one of my favorite characters in all of Hunter x Hunter, and although he is confusing to understand at times, we have seen how he has been able to stay in the fight using his intellect and physical abilities in addition to his Hatsu, even against some of the most powerful opponents we have seen in the series, such as Youpi and Pouf. In addition, the understanding of Nen that Knuckle gives us is easy to undervalue, since thanks to him, its incredible magic system is understood more deeply.$grulla$, $grulla$Knuckle$grulla$),
  ('cmnn876d9000zcndeo7n245tl', $grulla$Master figures are essential to most Shonen. These characters are crucial for characterizing the protagonists, and through them a great deal of exposition is delivered about how the world of these series works. However, the potential of these characters to motivate or change the protagonists is rarely used to the fullest, given the close ties between them and their masters, and when this is executed perfectly, as Hunter x Hunter does with Kite and Gon, it becomes something unforgettable, and one of the most important pivot points we have seen in the world of Shonen. In this video, we will explore the character and Nen abilities of Kite, Gon's master figure, and try to understand why his death had the impact it did on our protagonist.

Kite is severe and stoic, occasionally blunt to the point of seeming rude. Although some may consider him cold, he is actually caring; he likes animals just as much as people. However, he never hesitates, not even when he must take a life, even if he dislikes it: in fact, after saving Gon, he struck him because his ignorance led to the death of a Foxbear.

It is clear how Kite has an extremely pronounced paternal side, and we could even say he is Gon's real father figure in addition to being his master, which explains the attachment the boy has to him. Ging's abandonment of Gon, and the time Gon spent in his childhood with Kite, marked him deeply, shaping his personality, which demonstrates Kite's ability to influence others.

What is interesting is that even after his death at the hands of Pitou, and the consequences this had for Gon, we see another side of Kite following his reincarnation as a Chimera Ant. During her initial introduction as the Queen's last offspring, Kite is presented as an enthusiastic little girl, still playing with stuffed toys and swords, and still being cared for by Colt. However, after only a few days, she matured and seemed to return to her former personality as a result of recovering her memories. She then helped both Koala and Gon to ease their feelings of guilt and gave the former a new purpose in life, although she framed it as a threat. This demonstrates not only her compassion and influence once again, but also her analytical skill and tactical intelligence.

In terms of power level, Kite is one of the strongest Hunters we know of, with extremely interesting abilities. He is not only an expert swordsman, as demonstrated by his skill with his Tachi, or elongated Katana, but he is also capable of fighting with a varied range of weapons, as demonstrated by his hatsu, which we will discuss shortly.

Kite, like Gon, is greatly appreciated by animals, a trait that, according to Ging, identifies a good Hunter. In the few years after passing the exam, he discovered 68 new species. One of his most impressive achievements, however, remains tracking down his master, the elusive Ging Freecss. His competence allowed him to mentor a group of amateur Hunters, as well as to guide novice Hunters like Gon and Killua. While they were in NGL, Killua observed that he and Gon together were weaker than a one-armed Kite. Kite could effortlessly defeat high-ranking Chimera Ants, organisms he had never encountered before, and even managed to inflict some superficial wounds on the newborn Neferpitou with only one arm, though at the cost of his life. When he was revived as a corpse, Shoot and Knuckle had to cooperate to defeat him and considered him a difficult adversary.

As for his Nen, Kite is a Conjurer with a dual affinity toward Transmutation. Given that he was trained in Nen by Ging, one of the best Nen users in the world, it can be assumed that Kite is highly proficient in this field. He is known to have a powerful aura. His En has a radius of about 45 meters, with fluctuations of 2 or 3 meters depending on his physical and mental condition, and he appears to be capable of masking it with In, since Gon and Killua were unable to notice that he was using the technique.

Kite's Hatsu is called Crazy Slots.

Kite can conjure a variety of weapons with a clown-shaped Nen beast attached to them. A slot machine appears on the clown's tongue with numbers from 1 to 9, each corresponding to a specific weapon. Whatever number appears randomly, the weapon corresponding to that number is conjured, which means that Kite cannot choose which weapon to summon. He included this restriction in order to increase the power of the individual weapons. The summoned weapon will not disappear until it has been used. The clown can also speak and comment on Kite's actions and conditions, usually to his annoyance. Only three of his weapons are shown in the manga: a scythe, a rifle, and a mace. Additionally, according to Ging, the Crazy Slots ability has a number that only appears when Kite desperately does not want to die. This ability is interesting because it demonstrates that his power is so great that Kite managed to reincarnate as the Queen's daughter after his death.

Let's talk about the known numbers:

Number 2: Silent Waltz

Kite conjures a very sharp and enormous scythe. It cannot be dismissed until Kite uses it against his opponent.

After increasing the size of the blade, Kite swings it in a circle, generating an invisible cut that spreads in all directions. When he used it against the Chimera Ants, he split them all in half and knocked down the trees around them.

The scythe is not one of Kite's preferred weapons, and he considers it a poor choice overall, which is strange considering his skill with the sword. However, even though it is a weapon he dislikes, he turns out to be extremely skilled and lethal with it.

Number 3: Mace

Kite conjures a mace or a staff with a clown's appearance, which he seems to wield with a reverse grip. The true orientation and function of this weapon are still largely unknown. However, the clown refers to it as a "good number," probably referring to its simplicity of use and attack power.

Number 4: Rifle

Kite conjures a firearm with a shape similar to a long-barreled pistol combined with an extremely long stock. It can fire powerful bullets in rapid succession and apparently without making any noise. The long front element of the weapon appears to be some kind of silencer, which explains the lack of noise when firing. This is one of Kite's few ranged weapons, and he appears to be just as skilled with it as with his close-range weapons.

We cannot forget the conditions for using his abilities: he cannot choose the weapon he is given, and the one that is summoned must be used before it can disappear. We can assume that these are his own conditions for strengthening the summoned weapons, in the same way that Kurapika did to strengthen his chains.

Sadly, we never learned the other numbers of Crazy Slots, so we do not know the full extent of Kite's hatsu or of his power level. Tell me in the comments which weapons you think would be associated with the other numbers.

It is confirmed that Kite lost his Nen abilities after his rebirth. However, it is not confirmed whether this changed his Aura type, whether his abilities can be relearned, or whether he is even capable of using Nen at all in his new body.$grulla$, $grulla$Kite$grulla$),
  ('cmnn87641000xcndekpkhz447', $grulla$Every series worth its salt has those characters who are not merely supporting players helping to round out the protagonist, but who in many moments feel like protagonists themselves, being an essential part of the story and evolving just as much as, or even more than, their protagonist counterparts. These kinds of characters tend to be my favorites, and Hunter x Hunter gives us the best example of this with our little assassin from the Zoldyck family, Killua.

The key theme throughout Killua's entire character arc is the psychological concept of nature vs nurture. Nature vs nurture is a simple idea, but it has been an important topic of conversation in society ever since the question first arose. Nature has to do with genetics. It poses the question: are all humans and their behaviors a product of their DNA? Nurture has to do with the environment a person has had to live in. The nurture side asks: are all humans a byproduct of their surroundings and of the people they grew up with? Ultimately, the theory seeks to answer the question of how much control people have over their lives.

In Killua's case, understanding this concept is key, since it is the essence that drives his story. Killua is the heir of the Zoldyck family, a family of elite assassins who have been training him to be the head of the family since his birth. From the moment he drew his first breath, Killua has been subjected to torture, sent on missions to assassinate people, and forced to play psychological games with every member of his family. Being the head of the family is the only reason for his existence in the eyes of his family.

At the same time, Killua is also just a kid trying to find his own way in life. He was born with a good heart and is a fiercely loyal friend to Gon and to anyone else he considers a friend. Time and again, he proves to be a compassionate person who wants the best for those he cares about. Despite his own struggles, he has the endless motivation to be more than what others say he is.

The friendship between Gon and Killua is of the utmost importance to the development of both characters. Their mutual influence is tangible, especially as the show moves toward its final arcs. When the pair first meet during the Hunter Exam arc and up through the Zoldyck Family mini-arc, Killua simply wants to be Gon's friend. This is where the first great moment of his nature pushing back against his environment occurs. Killua hears that his friends have come for him while he is being tortured, and he frees himself with ease. He packs his things and heads to his father's room to tell him he is leaving. Surprisingly, he receives his father's blessing, and with that, he takes an important step on his path of personal growth.

The seed of his greatest internal conflict, that of his self-esteem, was planted in his childhood and slowly began to manifest during his time with Gon in the Yorknew City and the Greed Island isekai arcs. For example, at the end of the Greed Island arc, when Gon thanks him for always being there for him, Killua gets shy and turns away, thinking to himself that the roles should be reversed. Even though he has put a great deal of effort into the friendship, he still sees himself as being indebted to Gon.

In terms of power level and combat, Killua has been trained since birth to become a human weapon and is recognized by his family as the most talented assassin in the entire history of the Zoldycks. When he took the Hunter Exam for the first time, he was the fourth most powerful applicant (after Gittarackur, and, by his own admission, Hisoka and Hanzo). Up until the Hunter Exam, he wouldn't hesitate for a second to kill, but after meeting Gon this tendency diminished; even so, he is not afraid to resort to extreme means when circumstances demand it. Like his friend Gon, Killua has an astonishing natural talent that allows him to learn at a rapid pace and, supposedly, ad infinitum, a trait that sparked Hisoka's interest. His potential extends to Nen as well, as pointed out by Wing and Bisky. Although he fights mainly with his bare hands, Killua can use any kind of weapon, but the only one he consistently employs are his custom-made yo-yos. When he tried to prevent the Selection, he was so confident in his strength that he claimed tanks and fighter jets would be useless against him, and indeed, he was able to effortlessly subdue a military unit made up of at least four tanks.

His training granted him near immunity to poison, a high tolerance for electricity, great agility and physical strength, advanced armed and unarmed combat techniques, and stealth techniques, all of which he acquired at a very young age. He can also drive vehicles of any kind, including aircraft. His exceptional intellect and analytical skills are equally remarkable, and it is often through strategy that he can defeat opponents who are stronger or more experienced than he is. He is also capable of walking without making a sound and sleeping with a larger portion of his brain awake than normal, so that he can avoid attacks even while asleep, even if they come from a fellow armed, though weaker, Hunter. After leaving Greed Island, due to his prowess in Nen, Killua became able to blend in with nature more easily.

Killua's main weakness used to be an inferiority complex that paralyzed him with fear and prevented him from fighting opponents who could pose a threat to him, even if their overall strength was less than his own. Although it was originally believed to be a product of his training, it is later revealed that it was actually due to a Nen-imbued needle that Illumi had implanted in his brain. Its removal freed Killua from his brother's conditioning, thus regaining full control of his mental faculties in battle. This also had the effect of improving his overall movements, increasing his speed.

When it comes to his Nen abilities, Killua is a Transmuter with a dual affinity toward Enhancement. Killua is most efficient at changing the properties and shape of his aura. Like Gon, Killua's talent is said to be absolutely astonishing, found in only one out of every ten million people. Thanks to Bisky's training, he has refined his skills in at least two types of Nen besides his own, namely Enhancement and Conjuration. He has also mastered the four basic techniques and at least five of the advanced ones (the exceptions possibly being In and En, though he can extend his Ren to a radius of 57 cm to detect incoming attacks). He performed Ten successfully on the first try with almost no instruction, and learned Ren and Gyo in just one night. He was also able to perform Zetsu with great skill and without guidance after watching Gon use it against Gido, earning him praise from the Phantom Troupe, though they were able to detect him. He can maintain Ren for three hours outside of combat without the slightest difficulty, and Ten at all times. He can form Ko in an instant, as demonstrated when he used it to knock out Gon while the latter was going to fight Neferpitou. Although Gon can release a greater amount of aura, Killua is generally hailed as the one with the better control, to the point that when he faced Razor he was already able to distribute his aura with a margin of error of less than 1%, which led Bisky to comment that she only reached his degree of mastery in her twenties. Despite his lack of experience, he can accurately gauge how much aura to employ and in which area in a fraction of a second, relying solely on the instinctive knowledge granted by his fearsome potential. He easily surpassed Gon during their training on Greed Island, overcoming his inexperience with pure intuition.

Killua developed a series of Nen abilities in which he alters the properties of his aura to make it similar to electricity. This was inspired and made possible by the years of electric shocks he received as a child, both as training against torture and as punishment. Bisky was very impressed that he could create such a complex Nen ability at his age. He can electrocute his opponent either through physical contact or while keeping his distance, channeling his aura through his yo-yos or launching it in the form of a bolt. Although most Nen users take no damage from the electricity itself, they are still wounded and paralyzed for a few moments.

Killua has a series of special techniques that he employs through his electricity. These are:

Lightning Palm:

This is the most basic of Killua's Nen abilities, with which he uses his palms to electrocute his opponent with a shove. This paralyzes the opponent for a few seconds, allowing Killua or his allies to attack or escape.

Thunderbolt:

With this technique Killua jumps into the air and fires a bolt from his fingers, paralyzing the opponent and causing a good amount of damage. Although its power was not able to finish off even Rammot, we saw how it was strong enough to incapacitate Youpi for a few moments.

Godspeed

The first main function of this technique allows Killua to react automatically to external stimuli. Instead of the normal process in which the stimulus is perceived by the nerves, which transmit a signal to the brain, which in turn sends an instruction to the muscles, Killua programs his aura to send an electrical signal to his muscles to react instantly to a threat, thus bypassing the nervous system, which is comparatively slower. The aura can be preprogrammed to respond to different stimuli: physical contact, malevolent intent in the enemy's aura, or someone stepping into a predetermined perimeter, and the specific response is also preprogrammed.

Specifically, this results in a drastic increase in Killua's reaction time, which has both offensive and defensive uses. When Killua used a prototype of this ability, he was able to grab a dart the instant it was conjured, already in contact with his skin, and the moment it pierced him. The Whirlwind, as part of this ability is called, is also effective as an offensive ability. If the opponent executes the action for which Killua has preprogrammed a response, in most cases he will be able to attack before the opponent does, thanks to the fact that both his reaction time and his movement speed are drastically improved. When he used this application of Godspeed against Youpi, Killua was able to momentarily disappear from his sight and strike him several times without him being able to do anything, the brief lapse between the increase of the Royal Guard's aura and his action being enough for Killua to anticipate any move from his adversary. Youpi himself admitted to feeling completely helpless during the beating. On that occasion, even though his attacks inflicted no damage, Killua's electricity was powerful enough to provoke cries of pain from Youpi, as well as to paralyze him for a few moments. When he later used the same ability against Shaiapouf's clone, which is considerably fast itself, Killua was able to dodge its attacks with Komugi on his back, which led Pouf to fear that even with all of his cells, he would have difficulty catching him, and then he burned his cells by generating an electric current between his fingers each time the clone stepped on a circle he had drawn.

Since giving an order to one's aura is generally a Manipulation ability, it is possible, though unconfirmed, that Killua's Whirlwind uses this category of Nen.

The second application of Godspeed allows Killua to maintain conscious control of his movements. His running speed and jumping ability increase drastically, so he uses it mainly to cover long distances in very little time. As a consequence, this main function is more affected than the Whirlwind by the terrain: Tsubone could keep Killua in sight while he ran through the forest, but lost sight of him as soon as he reached a paved road. However, even at full speed, he was significantly outpaced by Tsubone's motorcycle transformation while she carried two passengers. The butler estimated that crossing the forest would take Killua about 10 minutes to reach a destination some 40 km away, while a car driver would take twice as long. This suggests that on unfavorable terrain, Killua's speed with his Godspeed is approximately 240 km/h.

As you can see, Killua's ability, although it appears to be quite simple, is supremely complex when we analyze how it works in its application of Nen, which perfectly reflects his development as a character. Personally, it is one of my favorite abilities, both for its use in battle and for how it reflects Killua's past and his way of fighting as an assassin.$grulla$, $grulla$Killua$grulla$),
  ('cmnn875sj000vcndeovuh0au4', $grulla$Cursed spirits are almost as important as jujutsu sorcerers when it comes to making the world of Jujutsu Kaisen interesting and giving it character as a whole. These innate antagonists have development almost as deep as the protagonists, and some of them show us ambitions, goals, and personalities that even surpass some of the good guys. Among them, Kenjaku's underlings are the ones who have been given the most screen time, and therefore the ones we know best, and none of them is as fiery and passionate as the unregistered special grade volcanic curse. Jogo.

Taking into account the wide spectrum of cursed spirits that have been shown in the Jujutsu Kaisen anime so far, there is no doubt that Jogo leans toward the extreme in practically every aspect. With a fiery temper matched only by the explosive power of his innate cursed technique, Jogo is a character who never walks away from conflict of his own volition, even in situations where he is completely outmatched.

In fact, alongside Mahito, we could say that Jogo is the most recognizable and iconic cursed spirit in Jujutsu Kaisen, and despite having lost the two main fights we saw him take part in, don't think for a second that Jogo is weak. What's more, excluding Sukuna, you could say that Jogo is the strongest cursed spirit we've seen; he's just extremely unlucky to have fought against the two most broken characters in the entire series. If you want proof of his true power against more standard-level characters, ask Nanami, Naobito, or Maki how they measure up against him.

Jogo is defined by his pride as a cursed spirit. He is an intelligent being who considers himself firm in all his beliefs, willing to give his life as long as his goals would be achieved in the long run. On a personal level, Jogo is always grumpy, irritable, and very arrogant.

Jogo believes that cursed spirits are the true humans and that they are the ones who will inherit the earth. He sees humans as creatures made of lies who try to hide their true nature with the positive emotions they display. Curses are composed of negative emotions, which Jogo sees as pure intentions, and so he believes that curses born from that truth are the purest forms of humans and that the false ones should be eliminated. To achieve this, Jogo and his companions agreed to ally themselves with Pseudo-Geto, or Kenjaku, despite him being technically a sorcerer.

Although Jogo is clearly an evil character, his relationship with his fellow cursed spirits is one of camaraderie, friendship, and even family. He sees Dagon and Hanami as his best friends, and his dynamic with Mahito is rivalry but friendly. This contrasts with his attitude when we see him as a villain, when he shows no mercy to humans, being arrogant while crushing them like flies.

In terms of power level, Jogo was one of several unregistered special grades that appeared around 2018. He was born from humanity's fear and negative association with volcanoes and other fire-related natural disasters. This resulted in a highly intelligent cursed spirit with massive levels of cursed energy, even for a special grade. Kenjaku generously placed Jogo at the same strength level as eight or nine of Sukuna's fingers. Although Jogo was no match for overwhelming powers like Gojo and Sukuna, he still far surpassed even the most talented sorcerers and other special grade curses.

Non-sorcerers catch fire in Jogo's very presence if he simply activates his cursed technique. Jujutsu sorcerers who enter his domain would suffer a similar fate. In Shibuya, the Zenin Team and Nanami considered Jogo to be far more powerful than Dagon, whom they had just faced with great difficulty. Jogo defeated Nanami, Maki, and Naobito in mere moments using his superior speed and power. This left half of Nanami's body charred, gave Maki permanent scars, and caused serious injuries to the head of the Zenin clan that soon cost him his life.

Despite not being able to match Sukuna with fifteen fingers absorbed, Jogo's strength was still acknowledged by the King of Curses. Sukuna admitted that Jogo's maximum technique could have hurt him if it had landed. Across all the opponents Sukuna has faced in over a thousand years, Jogo stood out as one of the strongest, a great endorsement of his power overall. Kenjaku even emphasized that he would have liked to absorb Jogo with Cursed Spirit Manipulation and acquire his technique, that's how powerful it was.

Innate cursed technique: Disaster Flames

This technique allows the user to form and control both flames and lava. Its capabilities are not limited to close combat alone, but can also be used telepathically, activating the technique directly on or near a target.

The flames are immensely powerful, capable of instantly killing non-sorcerers and seriously wounding sorcerers. These flames are also visible to non-sorcerers and possess properties similar to real flames. A person with superhuman physical resistance can completely survive these attacks thanks to their body, while a sorcerer's tolerance to curses might not be enough to save their life.

The technique also grants Jogo the ability to telepathically create volcanoes on surfaces. These volcanoes are capable of firing powerful lava at the user's target.

Jogo also has some named techniques that make use of his cursed technique, such as the Ember Insects, with which Jogo conjures small flying insects from his head, whose stingers produce a loud noise upon impact before exploding into flames.

Of course, we can't forget that Jogo is one of the few characters who have shown us the maximization of their technique, showing us the maximum technique, Meteor.

As its name indicates, Maximum: Meteor is a maximum cursed technique that conjures a flaming meteorite that Jogo launches as a projectile. It is relatively small compared to real meteorites, but massive enough to cause widespread devastation on the scale of an entire city. This technique is so powerful that it could even seriously wound Sukuna himself, who was forced to dodge it before finishing off Jogo.

Let's also not forget his domain expansion: Coffin of the Iron Mountain.

The environment built by this domain resembles the interior of an active volcano. It is a sealed stone chamber with large fissures in the walls and floor that expel large portions of magma. This produces such great ambient heat that the average jujutsu sorcerer would catch fire upon entering the domain.

Coffin of the Iron Mountain is a lethal domain that includes a guaranteed hit. The user can command the molten rock extending from the environment to strike his opponent with an attack that cannot miss; of course, if Jogo manages to land this guaranteed hit against almost anyone, his opponent would be instantly burned to a crisp. Unfortunately, when we saw him use the technique, his domain was overwritten by Gojo's, not allowing him to show its true effect.

Last but not least is the Domain Amplification that Jogo is capable of, a technique of manipulating compact domains that allows Jogo to amplify his cursed energy and form an aura capable of neutralizing the effects of a domain expansion's guaranteed hit. Additionally, this technique neutralizes the technique of whatever it touches, providing great flexibility in combat and, in theory, allowing Jogo and the other users to even strike Gojo through his Limitless. Unfortunately, this technique comes with a giant drawback, since it does not allow the user to use their innate technique while it is active, limiting them to hand-to-hand combat.

As you can see, despite his defeats and humiliations throughout the series, Jogo is a strong contender for one of the most powerful cursed spirits ever created, and his flame and lava control abilities are nothing to laugh at. Additionally, his development as a character, his personality, and above all his goals clearly explained to us as the audience make him a character who was incredibly interesting to see expressed in the work, and certainly make him someone relatable to many and even the favorite of some.$grulla$, $grulla$Jogo$grulla$),
  ('cmnn875hb000tcndevfvi9496', $grulla$There are characters that make us uncomfortable. Characters whose mere presence makes you feel that something is wrong, and that makes your skin crawl just from looking at them. These characters are usually physically grotesque and villains incarnate. However, Hunter x Hunter has my favorite example of this type of character, and not only is he not necessarily a villain, but he is the favorite character of many, many fans, and one of the most important in the entire story, both for explaining how Nen works and for the evolution of the protagonists. Of course, I'm talking about the sociopathic magician, Hisoka, the owner of the legendary Nen ability Bungee Gum, a technique with the properties of rubber and gum.

Hisoka is portrayed as someone completely selfish and self-centered; he does what he likes as long as it brings him pleasure in some way. His insatiable love for spilling the blood of powerful fighters in combat and his enjoyment of extreme pain while doing so feed his apparent sadomasochistic desires. So that the main protagonists can reach their full potential (in order to enhance the pleasure of killing them later), Hisoka allows them to live in situations where he could easily kill them. Likewise, he gets excited about meeting new people he considers worthy of fighting, or anyone with the potential to be a good fighter and entertain him in the future. The thrill of fighting strong Nen users in tactical battles and near-death experiences is an orgasmic experience for him. This is likely one of the reasons he goes to such lengths to find new toys to play with. If they break, he loses interest in them or kills them before setting out to look for more potential prey.

With his manipulative and self-centered nature, Hisoka is essentially a murderous sociopath. Although he likes Gon, Killua, and many others, he has said that for him, what is valuable one day could easily turn into garbage the next, and he will not hesitate to kill anyone if they don't meet his standards. He doesn't care about what happened in the past, since he is only interested in what could be fun for him in the future or the present. Although Hisoka's nature tends to be malevolent, he is not an indiscriminate killer. He has no problem killing anyone regardless of their age or sex; however, he only kills people who are in his way or those he considers "worthy." As such, his character is more simply amoral than completely evil. He even helps the protagonists if there is "fun" in doing so or if it will make them stronger, leading to a more entertaining fight in the future. Above all, Hisoka only cares about having fun and getting a good challenge, which may or may not involve killing people. He has a bad habit of skipping the Spiders' meetings. He can also be a capricious liar and tends to scare or play cruel pranks on his victims. Merely witnessing their uncomfortable expressions because he makes them nervous pleases him. His chaotic nature is inherent in everything he does and makes him dangerously unpredictable.

Hisoka has shown a morbid attraction to fighting powerful fighters, or people with Nen who have the potential to become strong, which is expressed through barely repressed murderous tendencies; neither age nor gender seems to influence his desire to fight them. He has expressed his desire to fight or kill random victims just to quench his thirst for blood. After his defeat at the hands of Chrollo, Hisoka's sociopathic nature has worsened, with him vowing to kill every member of the Phantom Troupe, even if they were defenseless, and stating that he will no longer allow his opponents to fight on their preferred terms. However, he temporarily spared Machi, who has been an implied interest of Hisoka's as a possible opponent he likes to flirt with or as a romantic interest, although he said it was so that she could warn the Troupe of his intentions.

Hisoka often exhibits androgynous characteristics throughout the series, manifested in his use of "feminine" shoes and a seductive speaking style typically reserved for women in Japanese. In the manga, he ends almost all of his sentences with a playing card symbol.

Despite his calm and composed personality, he can express his emotions comically in some situations. One example is when Gon, being honest and rather innocent, asks him why Hisoka was on Greed Island. Another example is his surprised face when he learns that he could not fight against Chrollo after Kurapika's Chain Jail.

Hisoka is famous for his elegant, cruel, and deceptive combat ability, which has earned him the rank of Floor Master, and he has proven to be a lethal adversary. His tremendous physical abilities and combat skills make him extremely dangerous in a fight, and his Nen expertise, tactical genius, and flexibility allow him to quickly adapt to changes in circumstances. Among the opponents he has defeated are the former Phantom Troupe member #4 and the Single-Star Blacklist Hunter, Bushidora, killing the latter without sustaining any injury. He has expressed dissatisfaction with the power level of most Professional Hunters, which led him to consider fighting the Zodiacs to find a new challenge, and indeed, he was able to effortlessly dispatch several Hunters in a short period of time. Illumi Zoldyck, who was estimated by the magician to be even more formidable than some Zodiacs, was careful about facing Hisoka, and even the leader of the infamous Phantom Troupe considered it prudent to prepare a strategy and gather Nen abilities before facing him in order to secure his victory, declaring that Hisoka set a new record for the number of abilities he needed to kill someone.

Hisoka is also a skilled magician and often uses Nen to perform his tricks. His skills in misdirection and his astonishing dexterity find applications in combat, and their combination allowed him to triumph against Kastro. This latter talent also allowed him to catch Togari's spinning knives on the first try, while their owner needed six months to do so. In addition, Hisoka has a certain degree of computer proficiency, which he used to track down Gon and Killua after they bought airship tickets online. By forming a circle with his index finger and thumb and looking through it, he can enhance his vision. It is unknown whether this technique is achieved with Nen, or whether Hisoka can simply enhance his sight by concentrating. Hisoka's enthusiasm for battle often causes him to take more damage than he would if he fought seriously from the start. In fact, his willingness to let Chrollo choose the place and time of their confrontation, as well as to adapt to his pace in the early stages, almost led to his demise.

Hisoka is a Transmuter gifted with a powerful and sinister aura that unsettled Wing and Gon even after the latter had learned Nen. He manifests his high level of skill in his natural category mainly through his Nen ability, Bungee Gum, but he has also proven to be very skilled at controlling the shape of his aura, which is a Transmutation skill. This aptitude may be what allows him to extend threads of elastic aura over distances of several meters without throwing them, which makes their application more subtle. He is also very well versed in Conjuration, the Nen type of his second ability, as well as in Emission and, apparently, in Enhancement. He uses the former to keep aura around projectiles, as well as in conjunction with Bungee Gum, to separate the ability from his body.

His affinity for Enhancement manifests mainly as a notable level of durability. Hisoka survived multiple Nen-enhanced blows from Kastro, an Enhancer, without using his aura to defend himself. Although he was briefly stunned, Hisoka suffered no visible damage from most of Chrollo's attacks, one of which can supposedly decapitate a person with a knife-hand strike, despite the fact that Hisoka could not predict them and was therefore unable to protect himself properly. He appears to have resorted to Manipulation on one occasion, taking advantage of the boost enjoyed by Nen after death to impart an automatic command to his Bungee Gum.

Aside from Hatsu, Hisoka is capable of using at least Ren, Gyo, and Ken, which allowed him to survive multiple explosions of The Sun and Moon detonated in his proximity, although one of his legs was severely mutilated. Like many other high-level Nen users, he can maintain a state of Ten at all times. He is also likely proficient in Zetsu and Ko. The two techniques he employs most frequently are Shu and especially In. With Shu, his poker cards can easily cut through bone and concrete even when he is not holding them. When he applied it to a severed human head, it carried such force that it pulverized other heads it came into contact with, incapacitated several puppets with a single throw, and injured a Nen user of Chrollo Lucilfer's caliber without sustaining the slightest damage, whereas it would break immediately if it were not wrapped in aura. While Hisoka prefers Shu for direct attacks, In is at the center of his strategies, as he combines the technique with Bungee Gum to set elaborate and deadly traps.

Hisoka's Nen prowess is further supported by his knowledge of more abstract notions, such as the strengthening of Nen after death and Exorcism. He also devised the concept of "Memory Overload" and a system for guessing an individual's Nen type from their personality, which, despite him calling it unreliable, has proven to be correct several times.

Hisoka's main ability allows him to make his aura sticky and elastic. Its extreme durability, flexibility, and adhesive properties make it an exceptionally versatile ability with various offensive, defensive, and supplementary applications. He can activate it from his fingers, hands, and feet. He can attach it both through physical contact and remotely, extending it toward the target, which makes it very difficult to avoid. He can command it to contract at will, and it retracts with greater force the more it is stretched. It is so resistant that it did not break after absorbing the full force of a ball thrown by Gon with Rock, or several of Gotoh's coins, which makes it an effective way to return projectiles to their sender.

Offensively, Bungee Gum can be used to draw the opponent toward Hisoka or to create flail-like weapons. He can also separate it from his body, in which case it will break after a maximum stretch of 10 meters. He commonly separates it from his body to attach projectiles to his opponent, such as his Shu-enhanced cards, while concealing it with In. The combination of this latter technique and Bungee Gum allows Hisoka to create multi-layered traps that all activate at once, killing the unsuspecting opponent in an instant. He has also emitted it to restrain individuals as powerful as Machi.

Bungee Gum also has a wide range of auxiliary applications. Hisoka can attach it to a solid surface to retreat at high speed when necessary. By using it on his feet, he can stick to the ground or run along walls. It is also useful for sticking objects in place for traps or for keeping them held down, even after throwing them. By covering a wound with it, he can instantly stop bleeding. On one occasion, he wrapped his lungs and heart with it to resuscitate himself. By creating non-adhesive aura, he can also replace lost limbs, which can be coiled like a spring to propel himself at tremendous speed.

Hisoka can apply his aura to any smooth, flat surface, such as paper or fabric, and manifest images on it to change its appearance and texture in order to deceive. He can replicate more than a thousand different textures. He has fooled Nen users of the Spiders' caliber with this ability, with none of them realizing that he had used it, whether by sight or by touch. Against Kastro, he used Texture Surprise to hide his wounds and confuse him. It can also be applied to pure aura, such as Hisoka's Bungee Gum, to alter its own appearance. Since aura cannot be detected once Texture Surprise is active, whether through sight, touch, or extrasensory perception, and its effects are also visible to people incapable of using Nen, it is safe to assume that Texture Surprise is a Conjuration ability, which is supported by the fact that it requires Hisoka's direct action to be dispelled and by a verb used in its description.

As you can see, not only is Hisoka extremely versatile and flexible in his thinking and actions, but his Nen ability perfectly reflects his character, being one of the most versatile techniques in existence. Additionally, in my opinion it is the Nen ability that best incorporates the base abilities, and Hisoka excellently demonstrates his knowledge in various situations, truly earning the title of a Nen master, in addition to pedophile, sociopath, and fighting addict.$grulla$, $grulla$Hisoka$grulla$),
  ('cmnn8758h000rcnde5orn3ezg', $grulla$Something we don't see much of in Jujutsu Kaisen is those characters who are completely disillusioned with the reality of the world, and how this entirely shapes their personality and motivations. A clear example is Geto, but aside from him few characters have shown us this kind of change. Recently, however, Hiromi Higuruma has shown us what it means to go from being an idealist to completely losing faith in the system he is part of, and his story reveals the complexity that exists even within the most upright of men when they are pushed to their moral limits, while his cursed techniques are an excellent thematic complement to his character.

Higuruma is one of the most complex characters in the entire series. As a defense attorney, Higuruma was renowned for his extraordinary intellect and his willingness to take on impossible cases in order to defend the unjustly accused. He strove to uphold the ideal that everyone deserves a fair trial under the law. However, when the justice system failed one of Higuruma's clients in a way that deeply shook his beliefs, it triggered changes within the lawyer.

Born in Tokyo, Higuruma began his career as a defense attorney, specializing in impossible cases where his clients were almost certain to be found guilty. Those closest to him considered him a bit of a masochist for taking on such difficult trials, but it was his passion for justice that drove him. With an extraordinarily brilliant mind that earned him praise even in the rigorous world of law school, Higuruma truly believed in protecting the innocent and giving even the accused a chance to prove reasonable doubt.

Over time, the nature of the work and the constant exposure to unjust verdicts took a toll on his mental state. Although he always tried to keep cases from affecting him personally, the expressions of horror on his clients' faces when they were found guilty despite overwhelming evidence in their favor haunted Higuruma. It became too much to ignore after his cursed techniques abruptly manifested during a trial in which clear evidence proved his client's innocence, yet they were declared guilty all the same. This pivotal moment marked a turning point that led Higuruma down a much darker path.

When his most recent client was found guilty despite the overwhelming evidence in their favor, it represented a failure of the justice system that Higuruma had devoted his career to defending. Still trying to come to terms with his newfound jujutsu abilities, Hiromi reacted with anger and pain, attacking the prosecutor and the judge in a moment of rage. This tragic event weighed heavily on him, as taking a life went against his moral code. It marked a shift in his perspective, leaving him disillusioned with the laws of man and disconnected from his former role as a defense attorney. He became generally discontent and detached from society, claiming that he now cared little for anything.

It was during the Culling Game, however, that Higuruma's character underwent another change. Initially viewing it as a way to simply observe how the rules might unfold without restrictions, he encountered Yuji Itadori and rejected his request for points to help stop the game. This set them on a collision course as antagonists. However, Yuji's willingness to confess to a crime he was not guilty of resonated with Higuruma's sense of justice, reminding him of why he became a lawyer in the first place.

With Yuji's innocence mirroring that of his client, who had faced unjust punishment, the former defense attorney had a change of heart. He reoriented himself to once again prioritize protecting the weak. Higuruma's cooperation with Yuji marked an intriguing change that showcased the complexity within this multifaceted Jujutsu Kaisen character.

Upon entering the arena of the Culling Game, Higuruma quickly distinguished himself as one of the best players. With barely any jujutsu experience aside from what he acquired in the short time since his awakening, Higuruma reached a level comparable to that of Grade 1 sorcerers in just twelve days. He exorcised numerous curses and killed at least twenty opponents within the colony.

It was there that he first crossed paths with Yuji. After Higuruma had Judgeman confiscate Yuji's cursed energy and perceived his disadvantage, the powerful sorcerer attacked with lethal intent. Yuji only managed to save himself by demanding a retrial, which halted their battle. This dangerous situation showcased Higuruma's combat prowess and his willingness to eliminate any threat.

From that moment on, Higuruma cooperated with Yuji's goal of stopping the Culling Game, even using his accumulated points to help save trapped civilians. Although they briefly parted ways to atone for their past crimes, Higuruma proved to be a valuable, if unstable, ally with potentially world-class abilities. His interactions with Yuji revealed new depths to this complex character in the series.

At the core of Hiromi's abilities lie his tremendous cursed energy and sharp intellectual talents, having unlocked his powers through natural talent and rapid self-teaching.

His cursed technique is called Judgeman, and it is thematically appropriate given his former profession. Using his vast amount of cursed energy, Higuruma summons a single Shikigami with a terrifying appearance, clearly based on a macabre version of the personification of the law. This shikigami features a set of scales, through which it can measure the opponent's guilt in an arbitrary crime that Higuruma decides to accuse them of. On its own, this technique does not seem to have much practical use; however, in a rather curious case, Higuruma appears to have awakened his domain expansion simultaneously with his cursed technique, and it is this domain that makes his technique and shikigami extremely terrifying.

Within his domain expansion, Deadly Sentence, Hiromi summons his judge shikigami. The domain takes the form of a circular courtroom, with guillotines surrounding a central stage. As the "judge," Hiromi interrogates his opponents while Judgeman observes passively, its verdicts influencing the conditions within the battle. Once an opponent is "convicted," Hiromi gains an advantage by increasing the size of his cursed weapon, the judge's gavel, which he wields with expert martial skill.

This domain is unusual in that it does not contain a guaranteed hit; instead, those trapped within it must follow the domain's rules, which include a complete prohibition of violence inside it. The domain includes a binding vow that requires Higuruma to explain the rules of the trial. First, Judgeman announces the charges against the accused, which can arbitrarily be things they may or may not have done; of course, Judgeman is relatively omnipotent within the domain and already knows whether the accused is guilty or not.

Higuruma will then lay out his case for why his opponent is guilty, and the accused will have the options of remaining silent, confessing, or denying the accusation and presenting their arguments. Should they choose the last option, they will not be able to lie. There is also the complication of an envelope containing additional evidence, which is only revealed at the end of the trial and may change Judgeman's verdict. In the end, if the accused is found guilty, they will then be punished with one of multiple sentences according to the severity of the case. These range from losing all of their cursed energy to the death sentence, which takes the form of a sword of light that will kill anyone it comes into contact with. It is important to mention that if the case is serious enough, both sentences can be handed down at once.

A curious case is that the accused can request a retrial if they believe the verdict was unjust and was made without all the available evidence, which, for example, allowed Yuji to use this for a retrial with Sukuna as co-defendant.

What truly sets Higuruma apart is his genius-level intelligence and his ability to achieve mastery of jujutsu in just two weeks, including barrier techniques. This rapid self-teaching allowed him to develop his own unique domain expansion, demonstrating his immense potential and love for the law.

Throughout the world of Jujutsu Kaisen, Higuruma emerges as one of the most fascinating characters in the series. Starting out as a passionate defender of justice who later becomes disillusioned, he undergoes compelling changes in ideology and loyalty. Although volatile after being betrayed by the justice system he had dedicated his career to defending, Higuruma demonstrates nuanced layers beneath an initial antagonism.

His change of heart and cooperation with Yuji reveal deeper principles of protecting the vulnerable, which first awakened jujutsu in Higuruma. Powerful yet intelligent, threatening yet vulnerable, Higuruma intrigues through a complex humanity. He embodies how even the most disheartened can find purpose and redemption. In a story that celebrates both the shadow and the light of humanity, Hiromi Higuruma stands out profoundly as one of the greatest achievements in character development in Jujutsu Kaisen.$grulla$, $grulla$Higuruma$grulla$),
  ('cmnn874zr000pcnde3vkb53fo', $grulla$We've talked a lot on this channel about how rare it is for a sorcerer in Jujutsu Kaisen to be able to use Reverse Cursed Technique to heal themselves or others. This ability seems to be reserved for the most powerful innate sorcerers, and it's clear how it gives them an edge in combat by letting them push past their limits again and again. However, with the possible exception of Shoko, none of the sorcerers who use Reverse Cursed Technique turn it into the centerpiece of their arsenal, or blend it with their innate cursed technique to make it viable. Or at least that would be the case if we set Iori Hazenoki aside.

Hazenoki isn't a main antagonist in the series; in fact, you could say he's relatively inconsequential and minor. Even so, his technique, and specifically its application alongside Reverse Cursed Technique, is one of the most creative uses of cursed energy we've seen in Jujutsu. This ancient sorcerer was, like many others, reincarnated by Kenjaku into a new body for the Culling Games, where he proved to be quite strong by showing he was on Megumi's level. Unfortunately, both Takaba and Kenjaku demonstrated the gap between their techniques and Hazenoki's, and we weren't able to see much detail about his character. The little we know about him has to do with his personality, which seems to be a product of the era he originally comes from. Hazenoki is one of the most aggressive and brutal sorcerers we've seen in the Culling Games, and he seems to enjoy torturing his opponents. Hazenoki's violent tendencies are both an advantage and a disadvantage, making him incredibly capable of inflicting pain and finishing off his opponents, but at the same time leaving him easily enraged and prone to losing his sanity against an opponent who can exploit his personality.

In terms of power level, Hazenoki's knowledge of jujutsu is quite extensive, and he can easily figure out the abilities of most of his opponents, in addition to being able to mix different techniques into his combat skills. Perhaps his most important trait in a fight is his high tolerance for pain, which allows him to get the most out of his cursed technique. Combined with his sadistic personality and his blinding rage that allows him to kill anyone without thinking twice, this makes him someone quite volatile and dangerous.

As I mentioned at the beginning, Hazenoki is able to use Reverse Cursed Technique, which means he can produce a large amount of positive cursed energy. The understanding required for this energy manipulation is quite deep, which demonstrates his knowledge, and the large amount of cursed energy he can produce allows him to keep fighting long after a normal sorcerer would usually have collapsed from exhaustion.

However, his innate cursed technique, Explosive Flesh, is what sets him apart from other psychopaths in the series. Using this technique, Hazenoki can detonate parts of his own body from a distance and use them as bombs. He normally does this by tearing out his eyes or teeth and using them as explosive projectiles that go off on impact with his opponent. Of course, this is what I meant by the synergy between his Reverse Cursed Technique and his Explosive Flesh, since it allows Hazenoki to instantly regenerate the parts of his body, effectively giving him infinite grenades. Hazenoki's personality and pain tolerance are also quite key to using his technique, since without either of these two, the sorcerer wouldn't be able to overcome the mental barrier of having to tear off a part of his own body in order to use his technique.

Although powerful and consistent, Explosive Flesh doesn't seem to be too devastating, since we've seen multiple people survive its explosions relatively unscathed. And of course, the synergy between his techniques is his greatest weakness, since his Explosive Flesh becomes useless without his Reverse Cursed Technique, which ultimately led to his end at the hands of Kenjaku, who disabled his ability to heal below the neck by attacking his spine.

As you can see, Hazenoki isn't the most complex character in the world. Even so, the creativity and the way he uses his techniques warranted this short discussion about him, since he showed us how a relatively minor character can hold some of the best ideas and concepts of this incredibly versatile power system.$grulla$, $grulla$Hazenoki$grulla$),
  ('cmnn874qr000ncndeequej97e', $grulla$Cursed spirits in Jujutsu Kaisen are naturally regarded as the source of all evil, being physical representations of human fears. However, throughout the story, the special grade cursed spirits, and especially those in the group of natural disasters, have shown us almost human motivations and goals we can identify with as an audience, such as brotherhood, a desire for justice, and sensitivity toward other beings. Even so, none of them better represents what it means to be an almost neutral entity than Hanami, who at certain moments doesn't even feel like a cursed spirit.

What's interesting about Hanami as a character is that, since she is born from the human fear of the earth's natural disasters, her main motivation, despite seeming evil at first, can be considered by some as something positive. Hanami seeks to end humanity because humanity is slowly destroying nature. In a certain sense, Hanami acts as Mother Nature's force of vengeance, and you could say she is, in a way, the karmic force and the consequence of human actions in causing climate change. In fact, it is mentioned that her cursed energy doesn't feel like that of a cursed spirit, but rather more neutral, like that of a nature spirit.

Hanami is the kind of spirit who cares about the planet that humans have been abusing for thousands of years. She wishes to kill humans to sacrifice them and thus be able to be wise in a cleaner world controlled by cursed spirits who will respect the earth. Hanami believes in Jogo's ideals along with Dagon, since they want to replace humanity with cursed spirits because they feel that curses are the true humans.

In contrast to Hanami's peaceful convictions, Mahito has encouraged them to embrace their savagery as spirits. In the middle of battle, Hanami learned to follow her instincts and began to enjoy the thrill of the fight, which allowed her to push beyond her limits.

Hanami has a close bond with her allies, and in a certain way acts as the mother of the group, even stepping into Gojo's path to save Jogo and looking after everyone behind the scenes. This aspect of her personality has earned her the affection of the other 3 disasters, and even Mahito appreciates her quite a lot.

In terms of power level, Hanami is a special grade cursed spirit with an incredibly durable body, powerful cursed techniques that can control plants, and an unusual ability to hide her presence more effectively than others. She was able to catch Gojo by surprise and momentarily take advantage of Yuji's vulnerability by using her Flower Field and a wood monster to rescue Jogo. This was possible thanks to a combination of Hanami's high intelligence as a curse, as well as her escape abilities and hidden presence. Gojo himself praised Hanami's ability to flee, since they were able to evade the strong perception of the Six Eyes. Satoru even found Hanami much more threatening than the straightforward Jogo.

Hanami possesses an incredibly durable bark around her body, capable of shattering Miwa's sword on impact. She was also able to easily ignore Kamo's Slicing Exorcism attack even though it struck the side of her head. A clean cut to Hanami's leg with Megumi's sword likewise caused no damage. Even after being struck directly in her arm by Maki using the special grade cursed tool: Playful Cloud, she was sent flying but only suffered minimal damage as a result.

After being hit several times by Maki and Megumi in her weak points, Hanami was still able to withstand their attacks, recover quickly, and ultimately overpower them with ease. The most that the majority of the students could hope to achieve was to hold Hanami off long enough for more reinforcements to arrive. Only Yuji and Todo together managed to wound Hanami enough to make her use her full power.

Additionally, due to her nature as a special grade cursed spirit, Hanami can easily reinforce her body with cursed energy to regenerate lost limbs in an instant. The recovered limbs maintain the same integrity as the rest of Hanami's incredibly durable body. She can also regenerate her weak points, the eye branches, but not if they are completely compromised and entirely separated from her body.

Hanami also has a high degree of physical strength and can easily finish off a human sorcerer in hand-to-hand combat. Once Hanami finally closed the distance between her and Kamo, it only took a few blows to incapacitate the sorcerer. But it isn't her close combat that makes her fearsome, but rather her cursed technique.

Innate cursed technique: Disaster Plants

This technique allows the user to form and control a variety of cursed flora. Normally, its abilities are initiated telepathically, activating the technique at the user's side or near a target, but it can also be deployed from the user's body.

The plants created by this technique can vary in size, shape, and physiology. It is possible to form anything from simple flowers to giant wooden roots. However, the technique's flora is still made of cursed energy, which means that curse-like plants can be created quickly and deactivated instantly.

The technique also grants the ability to absorb the life energy of real plants in a floral offering and convert it into cursed energy for the user. This ability can provide a large boost of cursed energy.

In terms of destructive power it may be the weakest of all the natural disasters' techniques; however, its versatility for stealth and its ability to recover cursed energy, combined with Hanami's physical durability, make it a perfect technique to complement the plans of the other three.

In terms of named abilities, Hanami has a wide variety of techniques, although none is especially powerful.

The roots technique creates gigantic roots from the ground and allows her to modify the battlefield terrain, although they are quite slow compared to her other techniques.

The wood ball consists of a dense, compact ball that she uses to throw her opponents and then impale them with thorns.

The cursed sprouts are perhaps her most interesting technique, since they eat the cursed energy of anyone they attach to, growing and eating more energy the more techniques their host uses.

And lastly the flower field, which she uses to distract her opponents so she can connect with her other attacks. This technique is said to be the curse's weakest.

However, we can't forget her domain expansion: the Ceremonial Sea of Light.

Hanami possesses the ability to cast Domain Expansion. The domain's guaranteed-hit ability is the beam that charges with Hanami's left arm. Hanami attempted to expand her domain during her fight against Aoi and Yuji after charging the flower on her shoulder with cursed energy. However, this was interrupted when the curtain keeping Gojo out dissipated. The technique looks fairly simple, allowing Hanami to fire a powerful beam from her shoulder and finish off her opponent in a single blow.

And don't forget Hanami's ability to use Domain Amplification, which is capable of neutralizing all cursed techniques or domains it comes into contact with. This aura or shield covers Hanami's body and even allowed her to eventually strike Gojo through his Limitless, although let's say it didn't go very well for her when she tried to use it in practice.

Despite the fact that, in my opinion, Hanami is the weakest in combat of the 4 natural disasters, her role on the team is very clear and important, being the neutral entity that keeps the others' personalities in check. Additionally, her inspiration and interpretation are the ones I like most, acting more like a karmic judgment than a simple cursed spirit that wants to kill just because. On top of that, although her techniques aren't too effective, their variety and creativity, allowing her to avoid detection even by Gojo's Six Eyes and to steal cursed energy, give her more versatility than those focused solely on destructive power, so we can't ignore this maternal entity of nature.$grulla$, $grulla$Hanami$grulla$),
  ('cmnn874hl000lcndeyvn99626', $grulla$As many of you surely know, power systems are especially interesting to me, and surely to many of you as well. Shonen tend to have innovative ability systems that deepen their characters, and they vary quite a bit in their levels of complexity. However, there is one that stands out from the rest, and that is even used as the foundation for one of the most praised shonen of the moment. Of course, I'm talking about the Nen of the acclaimed Hunter x Hunter. And what better way to begin talking about this incredibly interesting and complex power system than through the protagonist of its series, Gon Freecs.

Gon is an extremely interesting protagonist, because although he comes across as fairly typical in the early seasons, as the series matures we see how Gon begins to show his dark side more and more, until his psychological deterioration culminates in the Chimera Ant arc, specifically with Pitou and the death of Kite. Gon is easy to explain, since his techniques are quite basic for Nen techniques, and most of his combat focuses on his superhuman abilities of perception, endurance, strength, and speed, which allowed him to reach very high levels even before acquiring his Nen powers.

Gon possesses all the benefits granted by his status as a Hunter. At the start of the series, he had a fishing rod that he could wield with disconcerting precision, even managing to snatch Hisoka's tag from afar while the latter was moving at great speed. The fishing rod can also be used as an offensive weapon if the situation requires it. During the Hunter Exam, Gon was frequently praised for his observation skills, agility, and endurance. In battle, he thinks quickly to come up with alternative solutions and strategies. However, his most notable quality is the hard-to-measure and almost limitless potential with which he is gifted. Many powerful characters such as Hisoka, Wing, Biscuit, and Razor were astonished when they grasped the true magnitude of Gon's talent, which is often described as limitless. This allows him to learn extremely fast, especially in the field of Nen, where an aptitude like his is very rare. Even before learning it, he managed to use Zetsu on one occasion.

Along with his potential, it is his mental strength that continually leaves more experienced and skilled fighters perplexed, and it is a crucial component of his overflowing charisma, which draws even more powerful Hunters toward him. His indomitable will allows him to continually put his life on the line without being held back by fear, which in turn allows him to make decisions that others would never dare to make. Gon prefers to attack rather than defend, even sacrificing himself to deal damage, since his stubbornness tends to come out during combat. Because of this, he sometimes throws himself in recklessly, but at the same time he does not give up until he can no longer move. He is quite competent in hand-to-hand combat after being trained in the fundamentals of Shingen-ryu kung fu by Wing and Biscuit, as well as through natural experience. Although this quality often goes unnoticed, Gon can concentrate intensely even in the most difficult circumstances, noticing details that even Single-Star Hunters would overlook.

Other abilities he has include sleeping with a larger part of his brain awake than normal, thanks to Biscuit's training, and holding his breath for several minutes even when fatigued. After leaving Greed Island, due to his prowess in Nen, Gon became able to blend in with nature more easily, which allowed him to discover multiple new animal species at a pace that astonished Kite's companions.

Gon is an Enhancer and is therefore gifted with great strength and recovery abilities. Thanks to Biscuit's training, he has trained in at least two additional types of Nen, Emission and Transmutation, which he later refined enough to create functional Nen abilities. Originally, he displayed greater skill in Emission than in Transmutation, but by the time he met Kite in the former NGL Zone, he may have become more proficient in the latter category than in the former, as the combat potential of his Nen abilities suggests. Gon has also mastered the four basic techniques and at least five of the advanced ones (the possible exceptions being In and En, although he can use Ren to detect attacks he would otherwise be unable to react to). According to Wing, Gon's talent is found in only one out of every ten million people. He successfully performed Ten with barely any instruction, a feat Wing described as both "amazing" and "terrifying," and he learned Ren and Gyo in just one night. Under normal conditions, he was able to maintain Ren for three hours outside of combat without the slightest difficulty. With this technique, he could pulverize aura-strengthened objects thrown at him by a fellow Enhancer even in the early stages of his training. While trying to develop a Nen ability, he discovered the advanced technique Ko on his own after Wing suggested he show Tsezguerra everything he had learned at the same time, and he can deploy it quickly and in multiple parts of the body simultaneously. Likewise, he learned to use Shu simply by imagining the technique, and he succeeded on the first attempt. This means that, along with Zetsu, which he managed to use even before being introduced to the concept of Nen, this achievement qualifies him as a genius at Nen. Gon was able to discover three of the eleven techniques on his own. Although he was strictly a novice in that respect, he had some basic skill in reading an opponent's aura flow and estimating the amount deployed.

This, of course, allowed him to create his own Nen technique, the Jajanken, named after a game he plays based on the Japanese word for rock, paper, and scissors, "Janken," and the word "Jajan," or Ta da! Gon came up with the idea after learning the dangerous roots of the game within the martial arts. Jajanken consists of three parts. Gon's main attack is Rock, a simple but devastating blow that concentrates all his aura into his fist through Ko. His long-range attack is Paper, an emitted attack that fires a ball of aura from his palm; this used to be his weakest attack, the ball being somewhat slow, not very powerful, and easy to block or redirect for anyone using Ko. His mid-range attack is Scissors, a transmuted blade of aura attached to his index and middle fingers, capable of cutting through a Chimera Ant. Gon preceded each attack with the chant "First comes the rock! Rock, paper...", followed by the name of the attack. Since all three attacks were charged in the same way, Gon could decide to switch from one to another even after the preparations had begun, adapting if the opponent moved closer or backed away. Later, he became able to charge Jajanken even while running.

The long charge time made Jajanken difficult to use in real combat, although the risks it posed were the core of its power. However, through a technique called second round or Akio de, Gon is able to gather twice the normal amount of aura to use two Jajanken attacks in rapid succession, eliminating the need to perform the chant twice. The name of this technique was shouted after the first attack and immediately before the second. It is currently unclear whether Akio de was a different Nen ability or simply part of the Jajanken.

After the siege of the palace in the Chimera Ant arc, through a Contract, Gon sacrificed all of his innate talents to obtain immense power, with which he managed to defeat one of the Royal Guards, Neferpitou, on his own. He used this ability without any prior training; the only knowledge he possessed about Vows at that time came from Kurapika's explanation of his Nen ability. However, as a result, his body began to deteriorate shortly after the fight, and even after being restored to full health, Gon lost the ability to use or perceive his aura. Ging cryptically stated that Gon had only gone back to being "normal" and should consider himself fortunate, since he could have lost much more. It is currently unknown whether he can reacquire his Nen, putting an end, for the time being, to Gon's Nen abilities.

As you can see, despite the fact that Gon's technique can be summed up as a game of rock, paper, and scissors with different effects, the mechanics by which the technique works are quite complex and are rooted in how diverse and strong Nen is as a power system, so it is exactly what we needed to begin this discussion about Nen techniques. It is just a shame that we probably won't see him reach levels similar to what he showed us that fateful night with Pitou in the future.$grulla$, $grulla$Gon Freecs$grulla$),
  ('cmnn873yd000hcndenlhd7tnj', $grulla$---
The depth of the soul is not measured by what we hoard behind glass display cases, but by what we rescue from oblivion. In the ecosystem of _Gachiakuta_, the first season throws an uncomfortable truth in our face: we are what we throw away. But for the **Givers**, trash is not the end of a cycle, but the womb of a new existence. It is that spark of affection, that "respect for the object," that separates a mere collector from an artist of combat.

While everything may seem like trash in this world, the universe of the Cleaners and the residents of the Abyss is denser than it appears. Each Giver who appears in this initial stage of the story brings a distinct shade to the philosophy of "recovered value." It is not just about hitting hard; it is about how your psyche intertwines with inanimate matter to give it a purpose. Let us continue this descent into the dump to explain all the Givers and their Jinki from this first installment of the anime.


---
## Enjin: The Pillar of Connection and the "Umbreaker"

Enjin is the chassis that keeps everything from falling apart among the Cleaners. At 28, he is the mentor that the protagonist—and honestly all of us—needed. His name, which according to him comes from an ancient language, means "the person who connects others" (縁人), a perfect description for a leader who rescues broken souls from the dump.

### Umbreaker: The Shelter That Becomes a Drill

His Jinki, Umbreaker, is a worn-out umbrella. In a world where rain is a constant reminder of the Ground's toxicity, an umbrella is a symbol of absolute protection. However, Enjin transforms it into a tool of absurd versatility:

- **Defense and Flight:** Open, Umbreaker offers a solid defense and lets Enjin maneuver through the air, almost like a punk, rough-edged version of Mary Poppins.
 
- **Piercing Attack:** Closed, the Jinki becomes a drill spinning at extreme speeds, capable of shredding the armor of Trash Beasts as if it were paper.
 
- **Octa-Shredder:** A devastating technique where Enjin falls from a great height, unleashing a massive impact that can clear out multiple enemies in a single blow.
 
- **Long-Range Modification:** By using a cable, Enjin can throw his umbrella while keeping his distance, proving that his style is not just brute force, but tactical analysis.
 

Enjin is an enigma. Although his name is engraved on his Jinki—suggesting he uses it at full power—there is a constant suspicion that he is hiding something more. He is a pacifist who forbids his subordinates from killing humans, but who does not hesitate to use Rudo as bait if it guarantees a lesson in survival.

## Zanka Nijiku: The Pride of the "Average Man"

Zanka is the perfect example that genetic talent is nothing against pure obsession. Coming from the noble Nijiku family, destined to be Hell Guards (Guardians of Hell), Zanka grew up surrounded by "geniuses" who made him feel like trash. After being humiliated by Hyo, he locked himself in a pit for three days until Enjin found him clinging to a simple wooden stick.

His Jinki is called Lovely Assistaff (or Aibo, a play on words between "companion" and "love staff"). What was once a stick discarded by mistake is now a weapon of surgical precision:

- **Sasumata Form:** When activated, the tip becomes a restraining tool (sasumata) with blades and points that can impale and restrain enemies.
 
- **Vibration Detection:** By driving the staff into the ground, Zanka can feel vibrations in the area, allowing him to locate enemies even if his vision is blocked.
 
- **Extreme Mobility:** Zanka uses it to propel himself and perform chain attacks at supersonic speeds, a product of his hellish training with his sister Kyoka.
 

Zanka calls himself an "average loser," but it is that very insecurity that drives him to be the best at wielding vital instruments. His Jinki reflects his desire to be "useful" (Assist), but on his own "original" terms.

## Riyo Reaper: The Dance of the Assassin and "The Ripper"

Riyo is a bubbly chaos who hides a past stained with blood. At 16 and with inexhaustible energy, she was a hired killer before Enjin convinced her to change her life. Her design, nicknamed by some as a "Jet Set Radio punk," is deceptive; beneath her cheerfulness lies a lethal pragmatism.

### The Ripper: Scissors That Cut Destiny

Her Jinki, The Ripper, is a pair of gigantic scissors that she wields in a way that defies human anatomy: with her feet.

- **Acrobatic Style:** Riyo uses martial arts and acrobatic movements to swing the scissors with her legs, creating massive cutting arcs.
 
- **Size Manipulation:** The scissors can change size to adapt to combat, allowing her to cut Trash Beasts the size of buildings.
 
- **Deflation Effect:** One of her strangest abilities is her capacity to "deflate" Rudo when he swells from an excess of Anima.
 
- **Stealth and Efficiency:** As a former hitwoman, perhaps her Jinki is not her most lethal weapon, since she literally has a gun stashed in her pocket, which we have seen her use with incredible effectiveness, despite Enjin's restrictions.
## 4. Eishia Stilza

Eishia is an important exception in the world of the Cleaners. She is, possibly, the most indispensable and humanitarian member of Janem. In a narrative saturated with "destruction with purpose," Eishia represents the "maintenance of existence." Her design, with those cables that look like external veins, takes on a much deeper meaning when we understand that her function is not to take life, but to keep it from slipping away through the cracks of the Abyss.

- **The Jinki (Vital Instrument):** A power cable that, far from being a conductor of death, acts as an external life-support system. It is the physical manifestation of technical empathy. While others use their Jinki to turn trash into weapons, Eishia uses hers to turn the soul's energy into medicine.
 
- **Character Analysis:** Eishia embodies silent resilience. Her role as a "healer" places her in a position of unique vulnerability and power. She is not a front-line fighter, but she is the one who allows the front line to keep existing. Her psychology must be that of someone with an iron will; seeing the constant damage her comrades suffer and having the ability—and the burden—to reverse it requires an emotional stability that few possess. She is the reminder that, even in the deepest dump in the world, caring for others remains a priority.
 
- **The Bond:** Her Jinki is the extension of her own nervous system connecting to that of others. When Eishia uses her cable to heal, she is not just passing along electricity; she is sharing her vitality to patch up that of others. Her Jinki symbolizes interconnection: no one survives alone in the Abyss. The power cable becomes an umbilical cord that binds the team, allowing the transfer of "charge" to close wounds and restore functions.

## Tamsy Caines: The Tension of the Cord and the Hyo-Hyo

If most Givers find a purpose of redemption in their Jinki, Tamsy finds a tool of manipulation. He is a character who operates on the margins, whose true face is revealed only when the knots are tight enough.

- **The Jinki (Tokushin):** A distaff that generates and manipulates thread of an absurd resilience. It is not for "fixing" things, it is for **entangling**. His ability to deploy these threads allows him to create an invisible web of control over the battlefield, in addition to tightening them to leave his opponents immobile and even without aura, and unraveling it to create an incredibly powerful area attack, pinning his opponents to the floor.
 
- **Character Analysis:** Tamsy represents the "surface tension" of loyalty. As an infiltrator of the Vandals, his role as support for the Cleaners was the perfect cover. While everyone thought he was "weaving" safety for the team, he was actually preparing the net to hunt them. His psychology is that of a patient predator; he does not need brute force because he knows that a well-placed thread can bring down a giant.
 
- **The Bond:** The use of a distaff is deeply symbolic. It represents the control of destiny. Tamsy feels superior because he believes he holds everyone's strings in his hands. His bond with Tokushin is not born of the desire to help, but of the pleasure of restraint. To him, others are simple fibers he can twist at will. The revelation of his betrayal gives Tokushin a macabre air: every cord he threw to "save" someone was, in reality, a shackle in potential.

## Delmon Gates: The Hydration of Rage and the Farmer's Dream

At the opposite end of Team Eager's moral spectrum is Delmon Gates. Delmon is the antithesis of subtlety; he is a loud, passionate, and deeply emotional man whose strength comes from a genuine love and a devastating loss.

Delmon's Jinki is a water hose, an object that in the context of the Ground is a luxury and a survival tool. Originally called (Thirst Extinguisher)

Delmon was not always a warrior. He was a farmer who worked tirelessly to fulfill the dream of his late wife: to see a flower bloom in the toxic desert of the Ground. The phrase "Grow big!" was his mantra as he watered his plants, and it is that will to foster life that awakened his Jinki. However, on the battlefield, this intention to "make things grow" turns lethal. Delmon can control the water content of any target that absorbs it. When he fires at his enemies, they swell up like balloons until the internal pressure causes them to explode.

Delmon's use of his hose is highly technical, employing different nozzles for various tactical effects:

- **Silent Nozzle:** Emits a fine spray that incapacitates targets without causing a racket, leaving them unconscious almost instantly.
 
- **High Pressure Nozzle:** Launches jets of water at speeds so extreme they can punch through concrete walls and dismember Trash Beasts.

Delmon's loyalty to the Cleaners is unbreakable because he sees in the organization the only way to protect what little beauty remains in the world. His hatred of the Raiders is visceral, since they represent the destructive force that ruined his farm and, by extension, his wife's legacy. Despite his "gentle giant" appearance, Delmon is capable of a blind fury if his comrades are threatened, which makes him the "emotional muscle" of the team.

## Bro Santa: The Supervisor of Peace and the Tension of the Adoptive Family

The structure of the Cleaners includes units like Team Child, designed to handle younger Givers or those with abilities that require specific supervision. At the head of this team is Bro Santa, a 35-year-old man who personifies paternal responsibility in an environment where childhood is an almost nonexistent concept.

### Cloth (Cross): The Headband as a Bond of Unity

Bro's Jinki is a piece of cloth that he uses as a hairband, called Cloth (or Cross in some translations due to Japanese phonetics). This object is an Attacker-type Jinki characterized by its superhuman elasticity and resilience.

When Bro activates his Jinki, the cloth extends massively and his name appears engraved on it in the language of the Abyss, which shows that Bro operates at his maximum potential without the reservations that Tamsy displays. Its functions include:

- **Restraint and Lashing:** He can use the cloth as a whip to strike or as cords to immobilize multiple enemies simultaneously.
 
- **Tactical Mobility:** Bro moves through the environment using the cloth as a grappling hook, which compensates for his great size (195 cm) and allows him to maneuver with surprising agility.
 
- **Team Support:** One of its noblest applications is using the cloth to grab and catapult his allies, improving the reach of Dear's or Rudo's attacks.
 

### The Philosophy of the Supervisor and the Raising of a Giver

Bro is a firm advocate of peace and often apologizes for Dear's erratic actions, recognizing that children process the world differently. His relationship with Dear is that of an adoptive father who understands that a child's Jinki is, often, their only defense mechanism against a cruel world. Bro believes that once a child sets their mind to something, they can achieve incredible things, and his role is not to limit them, but to guide them so they do not lose their way in the process. It is notable that Bro hates sweets, an ironic contrast with his name and his role as "Santa," suggesting a maturity that rejects the superficial.

## Dear Santa: The Roar of Silence and the Paradox of Childhood

Dear Santa is, at 10 years old, one of the most feared combatants among the Cleaners. His design has been described by fans as a "Rugrats punk," with his two-tone hair styled into eight spiky tails and his oversized blue overalls. What defines Dear is his almost absolute silence and his dependence on a pacifier that is, at once, his greatest weakness and his source of power.

### Centralian: The Pacifier That Drains Existence

Dear's Jinki, Centralian, is his pacifier. In the context of a Giver, a comfort object like a pacifier suggests that Dear became a Giver in a moment of extreme vulnerability, when he needed to "cling" to something to survive emotionally.

Centralian possesses one of the most dangerous abilities in the Cleaners' arsenal: Power Drain.

- **Gathering Steam:** Dear starts every fight with the physical strength of a 10-year-old child, which is insignificant. However, with each blow he lands, his Jinki absorbs the target's energy.
 
- **Progressive Strengthening:** As he absorbs power, Dear's strength, speed, and endurance increase exponentially. A prolonged fight against Dear is a death sentence, since he grows stronger while his opponent weakens.
 
- **Comfort Sensory:** It has been theorized that the constant use of the pacifier is a necessity for Dear, allowing him to manage the sensory stress of battles and his own irritable nature.
 

### The Non-Verbal Warrior and the Connection to "Thought"

Dear only speaks to pronounce the name of his Jinki, which suggests that his Anima is so concentrated on the object that conventional language has become unnecessary for him. His temperament is volatile; he is prone to losing his patience quickly, especially if he is treated like a baby or denied his favorite snacks. His relationship with Bro is the only anchor that keeps him within the limits of civilization, and his rivalry with Rudo shows that, despite his immense power, he is still a child seeking validation and snacks.


## Guita Hebby Fantasia: The Fury of Plush

Guita is, possibly, the most "unsettling" member of Team Child. With a design that evokes a Splatoon character or a plush nightmare, this cyan-haired girl is sweet but completely deranged.

### Guita: The Onesie That Is an Organic Mecha

Her Jinki is her own romper, or Kaiju "onesie." Guita does not fight with external weapons; she becomes the weapon.

- **Kaiju Transformation:** When activated, her Jinki grows massively until it turns her into a giant monster capable of trampling Trash Beasts that dwarf the other Cleaners.
 
- **Plush Command Cockpit:** Curiously, Guita's body does not grow; she remains small inside the monster's mouth or head, "piloting" her Jinki as if it were a plush mecha.
 
- **Berserker Personality:** Despite her adorable appearance, in her Kaiju form she is a force of pure destruction, often limited only by her own erratic behavior or lack of attention.

## Semiu Grier: The Gaze That Precedes Destiny

Semiu is not just the receptionist of the Cleaners; she is the leader of Team Front and, possibly, the person with the clearest vision in all of the Ground. At 26, Semiu personifies absolute professionalism, although her hobby of reading adult magazines during office hours reminds us that no one is perfect.

### Eyes: The Glasses of Tactical Clairvoyance

Her Jinki, appropriately called Eyes, consists of her glasses. Unlike other Jinki, Eyes possesses no direct offensive capabilities against Trash Beasts, which places Semiu in a role of elite support and base defense.

- **Combat Clairvoyance:** Semiu can see brief fragments of the immediate future, which allows her to dodge bullets and projectiles with an elegance that borders on the supernatural.
 
- **Perception of Essence:** By concentrating, she can see the true nature or "essence" of a person, detecting any anomaly in their Anima.
 
- **The Price of Truth:** Using Eyes carries an extreme physical risk. If Semiu removes her limiters to fully synchronize with her Jinki, the recoil could leave her blind forever.
 

Semiu prefers office work not out of weakness, but because she enjoys the aesthetic of the "office lady," even though she is capable of knocking out a squad of looters all by herself.

## Remlin Tysark: The Spark of Succession

Lastly, let us talk about an honorary Cleaner. Remlin is the current Spellcaster of Canvas City, succeeding the deceased Gob. At 14, Remlin is a whirlwind of hyperactive, androgynous energy who understands that art is not just aesthetics, but a form of spiritual warfare.

### The Pen: A Legacy of Ink and Thought

Their Jinki is a fountain pen inherited from Gob. It is one of the rare cases of a "Succession" Jinki, which means it has accumulated the Anima of multiple generations of artists, making Remlin a "Natural Giver."

- **Art-Magic:** Remlin draws spells that materialize their feelings or intentions on any surface.
 
- **Protective Enchantments:** They can imbue objects or people with "protective spells" that reduce damage taken, even from blows that would be fatal.
 
- **Ephemeral Creations:** Remlin has proven capable of transforming aerosol cans into infinite fireworks or creating gigantic ink monsters.
 

Remlin lives by the motto of creative freedom; if it were up to them, everyone in the Ground would wear tattoos. Their ability to emotionally bounce back from the tragedy of losing their mentor into an explosive joy is what fuels the power of their strokes.

## Rudo Surebrec: The Vandal of Trash and the Touch of the Watchman

Lastly, and perhaps most importantly, Rudo Surebrec, our protagonist, is the epicenter of the storm. At 15, his life in the Sphere was an exercise in survival and ostracism due to his origin as "Tribesfolk." Falsely accused of the murder of his father figure, Regto, and thrown into the Abyss, Rudo did not fall alone: he fell with a visceral hatred and a pair of gloves that would change the rules of the Ground.

### 3R: The Gloves That Grant Purpose to the Useless

Rudo's Jinki, called 3R, belongs to the mythical Watchman Series. In the first season of the anime, it is established that its power is tied to the sense of touch. Unlike other Givers who bond to a single object, Rudo is an anomaly: he can turn practically any piece of trash into a temporary Jinki simply by touching it.

- **Versatility of Discards:** Rudo has transformed everything from broken keyboards to nail guns into lethal weapons. However, these objects tend to disintegrate after fulfilling their function.
 
- **Concentration of Anima:** His most technical ability allows him to focus the Anima of three different objects into a single one, multiplying its power by two or three (x2/x3) and altering its physical form for devastating attacks.
 
- **Appetite for Sweets and Fury:** Rudo is a protagonist driven by rage, but with a comic weakness for sweets. His combat style is raw and direct, reflecting his initial inability to process emotions other than revenge.
 

Rudo represents the concept that nothing is truly trash if there is someone capable of seeing its hidden value. He is the "Natural Giver" par excellence, although his emotional instability is the greatest obstacle to mastering his potential.

In the end, the analysis of these Givers forces us to reconsider our relationship with the everyday. In _Gachiakuta_, an umbrella, a pair of office glasses, or a plush pajama cease to be objects and become mirrors of the soul. Even secondary characters teach us a great deal: Semiu teaches us that seeing the truth comes at a price; Guita shows us that our childhood fascination can be our greatest weapon; and Remlin reminds us that art is the only legacy that can truly survive death. "Thought" is the only currency that really matters in the Ground, and as long as there are people willing to care for what others discard, humanity will have a chance against the abyss of the Sphere.


